# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bb-gun
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bb-gun/177-caliber] The **.177 caliber** or **4.5 mm caliber** is the smallest diameter of pellets and BB shots widely used in air guns, and is the only caliber generally accepted for formal target competition.
[src:bb-gun/177-caliber] It is also sometimes used for hunting small game, like fowl.
[src:bb-gun/177-caliber] It is also used in field target competitions, where it competes with .20 caliber (5 mm) and .22 caliber (5.6 mm) rifles.
[src:bb-gun/177-caliber] Steel BBs are typically slightly smaller than lead BBs at 0.175-inch (4.4 mm) diameter, although the bore diameter of the barrel are the same.
[src:bb-gun/177-caliber] Some air guns are designed to accept .177 pellets, .177 lead shot, or .175 steel BBs interchangeably.
[src:bb-gun/177-caliber] If two guns fire pellets of different weights, the gun firing the lighter pellet must fire it at a higher velocity to achieve the same muzzle energy.
[src:bb-gun/177-caliber] This is an important consideration in locations where air guns are legally restricted by muzzle energy.
[src:bb-gun/177-caliber] Because a .177 pellet is lighter than a larger caliber pellet of similar design, the .177 pellet can be propelled faster and therefore on a flatter trajectory, without exceeding the legal limit on energy.
[src:bb-gun/177-caliber] However, because the lighter projectile has a lower ballistic coefficient, it loses its initial energy to air resistance faster than a heavier, slower pellet.
[src:bb-gun/177-caliber] Therefore, a heavier pellet (typically of a larger caliber) may be preferred for hunting.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] This is a list of **laws concerning air guns** by country.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Most countries have laws about air guns, but these vary widely.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Often each jurisdiction has its own unique definition of an air gun; and regulations may vary for weapons of different bore, muzzle energy or velocity, or material of ammunition, with guns designed to fire metal pellets often more tightly controlled than airsoft weapons.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] There may be minimum ages for possession, and sales of both air guns and ammunition may be restricted.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Some areas in the world require permits and background checks similar to those required for firearms proper.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Air pistols are considered same as rimfire and centerfire handguns and subjected to Class H firearms restrictions.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Paintball markers are classified as "soft air weapons" and treated differently to other air guns; refer to the paintball section on legality for a state-by-state breakdown.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Paintball markers are classified in NSW as "recreational sporting devices" as of the 1st of July 2019.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Though also regarded as "soft air weapons", airsoft guns are strictly prohibited in all states except in the Northern Territory (where they are considered regular air guns and subjected to the corresponding laws and licensing) and the ACT (where they are considered "imitation firearms").
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Until 2010, air guns in the first group may be purchased by anyone over 18.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Air guns in the second group could only be purchased by people registered in the army, transportation depended on authorization, and usage was allowed only in places approved by the army.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Air guns of any kind may not be carried openly.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] There was no muzzle energy limit for any type or calibre until 2010.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Until 2010, scopes or any equipment with magnification needed to be registered by the army in the shooter's registry and accompany a traffic authorization, and were allowed to civilians only if under 6 times magnification and with the objective lens smaller than 36 millimeters.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Scopes with magnification equal or above 6 times and/or over 35 millimeters, or equipment that mark the target (like laser sights), were restricted to civilians and allowed only for use by the army.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] The permitted equipment has to be registered in the civilian's document, this process is called "Apostilamento".
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] The document for a shooter's registry is called "Certificado de Registro de Atirador".
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Since 2010, there isn't any restriction on caliber for air guns.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] It is now legal to own any kind of airgun, be It a springer, a PCP or any other kind of air gun, as long as the muzzle energy isn't bigger than 500 Joules.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Also, the restriction for optic devices for air guns were removed and is now required only in some cases, for military-grade equipment.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Since February 1, 2023, firearm ownership is now facing new restrictions, but there isn't any new restriction for air gun ownership – they can be used by anyone, and they can be owned by anyone over 18 years old.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Since 2010, air guns can also be used anywhere that is safe and the owner/tenant gave his permission.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] For example, the owner or tenant can shoot his air gun at his backyard, as long as he isn't committing a crime (if he is shooting late at night, he may be committing a crime if he is generating much noise).
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] It's still illegal to open carry an air gun, and even when someone carry his air gun in a concealed way of inside the case, he must prove his ownership of the air gun, likely with a copy of the receipt.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] All this information can be seen at the Brazilian's army website.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] As of 2024, the restrictions on caliber returned, albeit in a more mild aspect.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Airguns over 6mm caliber or boasting more than 500 joules of muzzle energy must be registered as firearms by a licensed sport shooter.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Launchers or weapons that are adequate to launch paintball balls are not subjected to the caliber restriction and do not need to be registered, even if they can also launch other projectiles.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Scopes, red dots and laser sights remain unregulated as long as they aren't military grade, but both airguns and optic devices need to be accompanied by proof of legal ownership (the sale slip/receipt) during use.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] The use of any gas/propellant, such as CO2, springs or helium, isn't relevant any longer, as long as the regulations are met.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Permitted uses of airguns include sports shooting, plinking at safe areas, training and authorized hunting of exotic fauna, as long as the other legal requirements for the hunt are also met.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Air guns can be freely bought and owned by any person older than 18 years old.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Only pistols with muzzle energy exceeding 7.5 joules (5.5 ft⋅lbf) are not allowed.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] There is no maximum muzzle energy limit for rifles.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] The use of air guns is restricted non-public places, being shooting ranges, inside a house or a backyard that is not easily accessible from the street.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] In Bulgaria anyone over the age of 18 can obtain an air gun if its muzzle energy is below that of 24 Joules.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] If is over 24 Joules the air gun subject to notification regime in the Police.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Cannot be bought online, but some gun shops deliver them with their own supplier legally.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Prohibit use and carry of minimum 200 meters from the nearest inhabited building or town/village.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Air guns with both a muzzle velocity greater than 152.4 meters per second (500 feet per second) and a muzzle energy greater than 5.7 joules (4.2 foot-pounds) are firearms for purposes of both the Firearms Act and the Criminal Code.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Usually the manufacturer's specifications are used to determine the design muzzle velocity and energy.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Air rifles that meet these velocity and energy criteria are generally classified as non-restricted firearms; however, some are classified as restricted or prohibited, depending on the exact design of the air rifle.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Air pistols are classified as restricted if their barrel is longer than 105 mm or prohibited if their barrel length is 105 mm or less.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] The lawful possession of these air guns requires that the owner have a valid firearms licence and that the air gun be registered as a firearm.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Such air guns are exempt from licensing, registration, and other requirements under the Firearms Act, and from penalties set out in the Criminal Code for possessing a firearm without a valid licence or registration certificate.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] However, they are considered to be firearms under the Criminal Code if they are used to commit a crime.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Low velocity replica air guns (under 366 feet per second) that are designed to resemble with near precision a firearm are considered a prohibited device and not permitted for ownership or purchase.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Under Bill C-21, mid-velocity (366–500 feet per second) air guns (such as airsoft and some paintball guns) that are designed to resemble with near precision a firearm would have also became prohibited.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] However, it was quietly removed from the bill and despite the bill passing, air gun laws remained unchanged.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] The simple possession, acquisition and use of these air guns for lawful purposes is also regulated by provincial and municipal laws and by-laws.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] For example, some provinces may have set a minimum age for acquiring such an air gun.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] These air guns are exempt from the specific safe storage, transportation and handling requirements set out in the regulations supporting the Firearms Act.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] However, the Criminal Code requires that reasonable precautions be taken to use, carry, handle, store, transport, and ship them in a safe and secure manner.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Carrying one of these firearms is permitted for those aged 13 or older.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Suppressors for all firearms, including air guns, are prohibited in Canada.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Air guns in Chile are unregulated and can be acquired by anyone.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Hunting with air guns is allowed, but only small game such as rabbits, hares and birds, and a permit obtained from Chile's Agriculture and Livestock service is necessary.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Air guns in the Czech Republic are governed by rules set by the Firearms Act.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Anyone over 18 can freely buy and possess an air gun with a caliber not exceeding 4.5 mm (0.177) and there is no restriction on muzzle energy or velocity, however bigger caliber air guns require a FAC or a hunting license.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] An expired hunting license is valid for bigger caliber air guns, as long as the license holder legally would be able to renew it.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] An air gun with a caliber over 4.5 mm (0.177) must be kept in a locked, approved gun cabinet.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] The acquisition and ownership of air guns is unrestricted unless they meet the definition of an effective air gun as defined in the 2015 amendment to the Firearms Act of 1998.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Any air gun that has a barrel diameter exceeding 6.35 millimeters or .25 inches, shoots metal projectiles, and was not manufactured before 1950 is considered an effective air gun.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Some provisions of the Firearms Act apply to effective air guns in addition to firearms, including the requirement to obtain a separate licence for each such gun.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] The possession of air guns in a public place without a valid reason is prohibited under the Public Order Act, as is shooting in a manner that disturbs public order or endangers public security.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Additionally, to permanently hand over air guns to a person under the age of 18 without the permission of their guardian is prohibited.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Under the Hunting Decree of 1993 as amended in 2019, air guns may not be used to shoot animals except inside a building to kill crows, common magpies, jackdaws, rock pigeons, and unprotected mammals other than feral cats.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Since September 2013, air rifles with a muzzle energy less than 20 joules (14 ft lbf) can be acquired by persons over age 18 and no licence is required.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] (Previously the limit was 10 joules.) For air rifles of 20 joules muzzle energy or more, a hunting licence or club shooting licence is required.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] However, hunting or pest control with air guns is illegal in France.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] In Germany, air guns producing a muzzle energy up to 7.5 joule (J) (5.53 ft·lbf) can be owned by persons from the age of 18 years and freely acquired provided they bear the "F-in-pentagon" mark that indicates a muzzle energy not exceeding 7.5 J (5.5 ft⋅lbf) kinetic energy.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Carrying air guns in public necessitates a carry permit (§ 10 Abs.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] 4 WaffG), extremely rare as such and never granted for air guns.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Only the transportation of unloaded and non-accessible air guns (or carrying unloaded during biathlon) is considered a "permissible carry" (§ 12 Abs.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Shooting is permitted on licensed ranges (§ 27 Abs.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] 1 WaffG), and on enclosed private property if it is assured that the projectiles can not possibly leave the shooting area (§ 12 Abs.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] The minimum age for air gun shooting in Germany is 12 years under supervision (§ 27 Abs.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] 1 WaffG), but exceptions may be granted to younger children upon request, supported by suitable references from a doctor and by a licensed shooting federation (§ 27 Abs.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Air weapons exceeding 7.5 J muzzle energy, e.g. field target guns, are treated like firearms and therefore require a relevant permit for acquisition and possession.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Proof of need, a clean criminal record and the passing of a knowledge and handling test are required (§ 4 Abs.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] The storage requirements for firearms do not apply to air guns (cf. § 36 Abs.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] 1 WaffG); they must only be stored inaccessible to minors.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] No power or Calibre restriction, Silencers and Scopes are banned by law.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] A Japanese civilian may apply for a license to possess an air rifle, a low-power gun powered by carbon dioxide, not gunpowder.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] The licensing procedure is not easy, and ownership of air rifles is becoming less common, in part due to how difficult it is to get through the licensing process.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] The process is time-consuming, and if you wish to own an air-gun, you must attend classes, held by the prefecture's Public Safety Commission.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] An applicant must be at least 18 years of age.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] The manufacturing, usage, and selling of air weapons (air rifles and air guns) in India are covered under the Arms Rule 2016, enforced through a gazette notification on July 15.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Before the rule got enacted, India lacked any regulatory framework on the production and distribution of air guns.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Earlier, even toy shops could sell air weapons.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Schedule I, Category III, Clause f of Arms Rule, 2016 classified air weapons into two categories.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Weapons having muzzle energy exceeding 20 joules or bore exceeding 4.5 mm (0.177-inch) belongs to category III(f)(i).
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Holders of weapons in this category require special licenses for possession and usage.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Category III(f)(ii) weapons have a muzzle energy under 20 joules and bore below 4.5 mm.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] There is no license requirement for category III(f)(ii) weapons.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] In the Isle of Man, air guns are treated in the same manner as conventional firearms and require a relevant firearms certificate.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Carrying air guns in public is illegal in Italy and it is a criminal offense to plink.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Air guns under 1 joule of power are considered toys and are unregulated.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Air guns between 1 joule and 7,5 joules are considered low-power firearms and so they are quite regulated but only require ID to buy.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Air guns above 7.5 joules require a license and are heavily regulated.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] In the Netherlands, air guns can be owned by persons from the age of 18 years and can freely be acquired.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Until 1997, there were limitations on muzzle velocity and kinetic energy, similar to the German law, but these restrictions were lifted for practical reasons.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Carrying air guns in public and the possession of air guns (and toy guns) that resemble firearms is prohibited.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] The expression "to resemble" is nowadays given a very broad interpretation so that just about any air gun can be considered to resemble a firearm.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Whether an air gun is considered to resemble a firearm too closely is decided by the police or, when it comes to that, by the court.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] It is impossible to predict the outcome of such court cases.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Air guns may be kept in private homes but must be inaccessible for persons under 18.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Commercial sales of air guns may only take place in licensed gun shops.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] It is illegal to own an air gun that was "produced or modified so that it can more easily be carried concealed".
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Generally, this is considered the case when the barrel has been shortened or the weapon has a folding or telescoping stock.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] In New Zealand any member of the public over the age of 18 may own and fire most air rifles without a firearms licence, provided they use the air rifle in a safe environment with a responsible attitude.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Minors 16 and over, but under the age of 18, require a Firearms Licence to possess an air rifle – however, they may use an air rifle under adult supervision without this licence.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] "Specially dangerous airguns" require a firearms licence for possession and use.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Such weapons are specified under the New Zealand *Arms Acts*, and currently include only some pre-charged pneumatic rifles.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] The change was made as a consequence of two fatal shootings by .22 calibre semi-automatic air rifles.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] In Norway, air guns can only be purchased by persons from the age of 18 years.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Although they can be owned and transported by persons under the age of 18.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] They can be freely acquired as long as the caliber is not greater than 4.5/0.177.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] There is no limit on bullet speed or energy.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] For larger calibers, such as 5.5 and 6.35, a permit obtained from the police is required.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] This type of permit is easier to obtain than a firearm licence.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Hunting with an air gun is not permitted; target practice is a common reason for a permit application.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] In Poland it is possible to freely acquire air guns with a muzzle energy not exceeding 17 joules (13 ft⋅lbf).
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Air guns with muzzle energy over 17 J are considered **FAC** and must be registered at a local police station no later than 5 days after purchase (a gun licence is not needed).
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] **FAC** air guns can only be used at officially licensed shooting ranges.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Hunting/shooting animals with air guns is illegal and can lead to prosecution.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Owning airgun after you obtain safety firearm course, police background check, medical psychological checks you can apply for self defence guns shooting rubber balls or gas with maximum of 2 guns or air rifles shooting no more than 200 m/s and maximum of 1000 rounds.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Exception of high powered air rifles is only for sport club members who can own air rifles with speed over 200 m/s.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] In Russia, according to Federal Law #150 "On weapons", any person who is older than 18 years old is eligible to buy an air gun in caliber 4,5 mm (.177) with muzzle energy up to 7.5 J without obtaining a gun permit and its registration in Federal Service of National Guard Troops.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Hunting air guns with muzzle energy from 7.5 to 25 J are needed to be registered in aforementioned service and require to obtain a gun permit.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Air guns certified as sport weapons can have muzzle energy more than 25 J and also require these procedures.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Air guns in any caliber with muzzle energy less than 3 J (e.g., airsoft guns) are not considered as weapons and may not correspond aforementioned law restrictions related to civil weapons.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] 4.5 mm air guns modification to acquire muzzle energy more than 7.5 J is an administrative offence according to the article 20.10 of Administrative Offences Code of Russia and is punished by a fine from 1000 to 5000 rubles with confiscation of an air gun.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] In Singapore, airguns are classified as 'arms', in the same category as firearms utilising gunpowder as propellant among other weapons.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] It is necessary to obtain a licence from the Singapore Police Force before one can import, export or own an airgun.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] a) of a calibre of **less** than or equal to **5.6mm** (.22 calibre); **or** b) at a muzzle energy of less than 8 joules (6 ft-lbs), by means of compressed gas and not by means of burning propellant;.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Airguns that shoot projectiles over 5.6mm (.22) in calibre and shoot at energies greater than 8 joules (6 ft-lbs) are classified as firearms in the FCA of 2000 (Firearms Control Act).
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] All classified firearms are required to be licensed in terms of the act.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] An airgun that shoots projectiles under 5.6mm (.22) in calibre has no maximum energy restrictions placed on it in the FCA (Firearms Control Act).
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Airguns still count as firearms if used in a crime, and can't be fired in public areas.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Airguns may be carried on one's person concealed/openly.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] It is an offense to shoot animals and human beings, except criminals and animals which are attacking you.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] This is defined in Chapter 16 of the FCA (Firearms Control Act).
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Update 31/12/2020 SAPS put out an internal circular to clarify the law with regards to Airguns and the current Firearm Amnesty.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Anyone over the age of 16 can obtain an airgun if its muzzle energy is below that of 10.5 Joules due to federal law.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] If is over 24 Joules the airgun subject to notification regime in the Police.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Legality and ownership of air gun weaponry depend on the power of the air rifle/pistol.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] If the power of the air weapon is under 24.2 joules, the owner must be at least 14 years of age.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] In such a case, the owner must obtain a legal document known as "Tarjeta de Armas" (Firearm Card) issued by the municipality in which the owner resides.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] If the air weapon's power is over 24.2 joules, the owner must be at least 18 years of age.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Or, if they are 16 years of age, the owner must possess parental consent.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] In this case, the owner must register for a "Licencia de Armas Tipo E" (Firearms License E Class) and obtain the "Guía" (Register of the Firearm).
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] The application and procedures are followed along with the "Guardia Civil" regulation covering age of consent.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Furthermore, the use of air weapons for hunting game is strictly forbidden.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Air weapon shooting and activity can only be used for sports shooting in clubs and regulated shooting events with adequate installations and safety measures in place.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] In Sweden, airguns are regarded as firearms and generally require a license.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] However, limited energy weapons, defined as having a muzzle energy not exceeding 10 joules measured four meters from the muzzle, such as airguns and paintball guns, do not require a license.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] They may not be used by a minor under 18 years of age unless licensed or the minor is under adult supervision.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Fully automatic limited energy weapons may not exceed 3 joules.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Hunting small animals such as rodents and birds for pest control purposes is legal.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] The requirements for hunting are that the shooter has a hunting license, the rifle has at least 180 m/s muzzle velocity, the projectile is at least .22 caliber, is designed to expand, and has at least 16 joules of impact energy.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Calibier limitation up to .25cal (6,35mm) and age restriction of 18+.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Air pistols generating more than 6 ft·lbf (8.1 J) and air rifles generating more than 12 ft·lbf (16.2 J) of muzzle energy are legally termed "specifically dangerous firearms".
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] As a result, ownership of these air rifles requires the possession of a Firearm Certificate (FAC); however, ownership of such air pistols is prohibited as they are defined as "Prohibited Weapons" under Section 5 of the Firearms Act 1968.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Pistols and rifles below these energy levels are still termed firearms and are dealt with under the *Firearms Act*, but do not require licensing in England and Wales, and may be purchased by anyone over the age of 18.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Pistols and rifles under 0.737 ft·lbf (1 J), including airsoft guns, are not included under firearms regulations in the UK, but do fall under The Violent Crime Reduction Act 2006.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] In Northern Ireland, any air rifle or air pistol generating more than 0.737 ft·lbf (1 J) is considered a firearm and as such requires a FAC.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] In Scotland, the Air Weapons and Licensing (Scotland) Act 2015 introduced an Air Weapon Certificate (AWC), which anyone owning or possessing an air weapon, the component parts of an air weapon and/or a sound suppressor/moderator is now required to hold.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] The application process for an AWC is broadly similar to that of a FAC and includes background checks.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] The Violent Crime Reduction Act 2006 prohibits online or mail-order sale of air guns by way of trade or business in the UK.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] UK transactions for items from retail UK shops must be finalised face-to-face, either at the shop where purchased or through a Registered Firearms Dealer (to which an item may be posted and the transfer completed).
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Since February 2011, the Crime and Security Act 2010 (s.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] This legislation essentially relates to the storage of air guns and the requirement of owners to prevent unauthorised access by children.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Failure to do so renders owners liable for a fine of up to £1,000.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Possession of an air gun while trespassing, with or without ammunition, loaded or unloaded, is treated as armed trespass and is considered a serious criminal offence subject to heavy penalties.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Two states (New Jersey and Rhode Island) define all non-powder guns as firearms; one state (Illinois) defines certain high-power and/or large calibre non-powder guns as firearms; three states (Connecticut, Delaware and North Dakota) define non-powder guns as dangerous weapons (but not firearms).
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] The remaining states which regulate air guns impose age restrictions on possession, use, or transfer of non-powder guns, and/or explicitly regulate possession of non-powder guns on school grounds.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] New York City has a restrictive municipal ordinance regulating air guns.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Air guns were previously banned in San Francisco, but a state preemption statute struck down the ban, and the San Francisco District Attorney declared them legal as long as they are in compliance with state law.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] New York state law prohibits anyone under the age of 16 from possessing an air gun.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Along with state laws, local county laws or ordinances may be relevant to users of air guns.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun-laws] Generally, state laws do not mention air gun laws, but local counties do.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] An **air gun** or **airgun** is a gun that uses compressed air or other pressurized gases to fire projectiles, reminiscent of the principle behind the ancient blowgun.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] This is in contrast to a firearm, which shoots projectiles using pressure generated via combustion of a chemical propellant, most often black powder in antique firearms and smokeless powder in modern firearms.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Air guns come in both long gun (**air rifle**) and handgun (**air pistol**) forms.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Both types typically propel metallic projectiles that are either diabolo-shaped pellets or spherical shots called BBs, although in recent years Minié ball-shaped cylindro-conoidal projectiles called slugs are becoming more popular.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Certain types of air guns (usually air rifles) may also launch fin-stabilized projectile such as darts (e.g., tranquilizer guns) or hollow-shafted arrows (so-called "airbows").
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] The air guns were first developed in the 16th century, and have since been used in hunting, shooting sports, and even in warfare.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] There are three different power sources for modern air guns, depending on the design: spring-piston, pneumatic or bottled compressed gas (most commonly carbon dioxide and recently nitrogen).
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Air guns represent the oldest pneumatic technology.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] The oldest existing mechanical air gun dates back to about 1580, and is currently kept in the Livrustkammaren Museum in Stockholm.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] This is approximately what most historians recognize as the beginning of the modern air gun.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Throughout 17th to 19th century, air guns in .30 to .51 calibers were used to hunt big game, deer and wild boar.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] These air rifles were charged using a pump to fill an air reservoir and produced velocities from 650 to 1,000 ft/s (200 to 300 m/s).
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] They were also used in warfare, the most recognized example being the Girandoni air rifle, a repeating rifle used by Austria in the 1788 war against Turkey.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] At that time, they had compelling advantages over the muzzleloader firearms of the day.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] For example, air guns could be discharged in wet weather and rain (unlike both matchlock and flintlock muskets), and discharged much faster than muzzle-loading guns.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Moreover, they were quieter than a firearm of a similar caliber and produced no muzzle flash or smoke cloud when fired.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Thus, they did not give away the shooter's position or obscure the shooter's view, unlike the black powder muskets of the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] In the hands of skilled soldiers, they gave the military a distinct advantage.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] France, Austria and other nations had special sniper detachments using air rifles, mostly Jäger (infantry).
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] The Austrian 1779 model was named *Windbüchse* (literally "wind rifle" in German).
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] The gun was developed in 1768 or 1769 by the Tyrolean Ladins watchmaker, mechanic and gunsmith Bartholomäus Girardoni (1744–1799) and is sometimes referred to as the Girandoni air rifle or Girardoni air gun in literature (the name is also spelled "Girandony", "Giradoni" or "Girardoni".).
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Adopted by the Austrian leadership in 1779, the *Windbüchse* was about 4 ft (1.2 m) long and weighed 10 pounds (4.5 kg), about the same size and mass as a conventional musket.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] The air reservoir was a removable, club-shaped, butt.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] The *Windbüchse* carried twenty-two .51 caliber (13 mm) lead balls in a tubular magazine.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] A skilled shooter could fire off one magazine in about thirty seconds.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] A shot from this air gun could penetrate a one-inch-thick (2.5 cm) wooden board at a hundred paces, an effect roughly equal to that of a modern 9×19mm or .45 ACP caliber pistol.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Circa 1820, the Japanese inventor Kunitomo Ikkansai developed various manufacturing methods for guns, and also created an air gun based on the study of Western knowledge ("rangaku") acquired from the Dutch in Dejima.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] The Lewis and Clark Expedition (1804) carried a reservoir air gun, very likely the Girardoni, as it held 22 round balls of .46 caliber in a tubular magazine mounted on the side of the barrel.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] The butt of the gun served as the air reservoir and had a working pressure of 800 psi (55 bar).
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] The rifle was said to be capable of 22 aimed shots per minute and had a rifled bore of 0.452 in (11.5 mm) and a groove diameter 0.462 in (11.7 mm).
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] One of the first commercially successful and mass-produced air guns was manufactured by the William F.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Markham's Markham Air Rifle Company in Plymouth, Michigan, US.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Their first model air gun was the wooden *Challenger*, marketed in 1886.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] In response, Clarence Hamilton from the neighboring Plymouth Air Rifle Company (later renamed to Daisy Manufacturing Company in 1895) marketed their all-metal Daisy BB Gun in early 1888, which prompted Markham to respond with their *Chicago* model in 1888 followed by the *King* model in 1890.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] The *Chicago* model was sold by Sears, Roebuck for 73 cents in its catalog.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] In 1928, the name of the Markham company was changed to King Air Rifle Company after the company was purchased by Daisy in 1916 after decades of intense competition, and continued to manufacture the "King" model air rifle until 1935 before ceasing operation altogether in the 1940s.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] From the 1890s onwards, air rifles were used in Birmingham, England for competitive target shooting.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Matches were held in public houses and working men's clubs, which sponsored shooting teams.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] This often took the form of Bell Target shooting, where the competitor aims to ring a bell by shooting through a small hole in a steel plate.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Prizes, such as a leg of mutton for the winning team, were paid for by the losing team.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] During this time, over 4,000 air rifle clubs and associations existed across Great Britain, with as many as 1,600 in Birmingham alone.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] During this time, the air gun was associated with poaching because it could deliver a shot without a significant muzzle report.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Air guns are used for hunting (small to medium game), pest control, recreational shooting (commonly known as plinking) and competitive sports such as the Olympic 10 m air rifle and 10 m air pistol events.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Field target (FT) is a competitive form of metallic silhouette shooting in which the targets are animal-shaped steel targets with a "kill zone" cut-out.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Hunter field target (HFT) is a variation, using identical equipment, but with differing rules.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] The distances FT and HFT competitions are shot at range between 7.3 and 41.1 metres (24 and 135 ft) for HFT & 7.3 and 50.29 metres (24.0 and 165.0 ft) for FT, with varying sizes of "reducers" being used to increase or decrease the size of the kill zone.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] In the UK, competition power limits are set at the legal maximum for an unlicensed air rifle, i.e.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Air rifle benchrest is an international shooting sport where the objective is to hit a (small) bulls eye target at 25 m (27.34 yd) shooting distance.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] There are two divisions ARLV 12 ft⋅lbf (16.27 J) and ARHV 20 ft⋅lbf (27.12 J).
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] The increasing affordability of higher-power pre-charged pneumatic (PCP) rifles has allowed large projectiles and further target distance for competition purposes.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] For instance, the Extreme Benchrest competition held annually in Green Valley, Arizona allows calibers up to .30 inches (7.6 mm) at 75 yd (68.58 m) while the Big Bore Benchrest arm of the same competition at other localities engages targets at 35 to 300 yards (32 to 274 m).
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] The component of an airgun that provides the gas pressure needed to propel projectiles is called its *powerplant*, which uses internally stored pressurized gas; and *compressed gas* (most commonly CO2), which uses external sources of pressurized gas.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] A **spring-piston air gun** (also known as a **spring gun** or simply a "**springer**") operates by means of a spring-loaded piston pump assembly contained within a compression chamber separate from the gun barrel.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Traditionally, a grease-lubricated steel coil spring is used as the powerplant main spring.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Before shooting, the user needs to manually cock the gun by flexing a lever connected to the pump assembly, which pulls the pump piston rearwards and compresses the main spring until the rear of the piston engages the sear.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] When shooting, the trigger is pulled and disengages the sear, allowing the main spring to decompress and release its stored elastic potential energy, pushing the piston forward, thereby compressing the air in the pump cylinder.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] All this takes place in a fraction of a second, during which the air undergoes adiabatic heating to several hundred degrees and then cools as the air expands.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] This can also cause a phenomenon referred as "dieseling", where flammable substances in the compression chamber (e.g., petroleum-based lubricant) can be ignited by the compression heat like in a diesel engine, and lead to an afterburner effect with (often unpredictable) additional thrusts.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] This often results in combustion smoke coming out of the muzzle and potential pressure damage to the rubber O-ring seals inside the gun.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Dieseling can be made to occur *intentionally* to increase power, by coating the pellet with lubricant or petroleum jelly, although this may result in damage to the breech seal.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Most spring-piston guns are single-shot breechloaders by nature, but multiple-shot repeaters with magazine feeders have been introduced in recent years by manufacturers such as Gamo, Umarex and Hatsan.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Spring-piston guns, especially the high-powered "magnum" guns, are able to achieve muzzle velocities exceeding the speed of sound.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] The effort required for the cocking stroke is proportional to the designed power of the gun, with higher muzzle velocities requiring a stiffer spring and hence a greater cocking effort.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Spring-piston guns have a practical upper limit of 1,250 ft/s (380 m/s) for .177 cal (4.5 mm) pellets, as higher velocities cause unstable pellet flight and loss of accuracy.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] This is due to the extreme buffeting caused when the pellet reaches and surpasses transonic speed, then slows back down and goes through sound barrier again, which is more than enough to destabilize the pellet's flight.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Shortly after leaving the barrel, the supersonic pellet falls back below the speed of sound and the shock wave overtakes the pellet, causing its flight stability to be disrupted.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Drag increases disproportionately as pellet velocity increases, so it is generally better to increase pellet weight to keep velocities subsonic in high-powered guns.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Many shooters find that velocities in the 800–900 ft/s (240–270 m/s) range offer an ideal balance between power and accuracy.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Spring-piston guns, especially high-powered ("magnum") models, do still recoil as a result of the mainspring pushing the piston forward.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Although the recoil is less than that of some cartridge firearms, it can make the gun difficult to shoot accurately as the spring recoil is in effect while the pellet is still within the barrel.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Spring gun recoil also has a sharp forward component, caused by the piston hitting the front end of the pump chamber when the spring has fully decompressed.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] These rapid double-jerking movements are known to damage scopes not rated for spring gun usage.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] In addition, the spring often has unpredictable collateral transverse vibrations as well as torquing, both of which can cause accuracy to suffer.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] The better quality spring guns can have very long service lives, being simple to maintain and repair.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Because they deliver the same mechanical energy output on each shot, external ballistics are quite consistent.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Most Olympic air gun competitions through the 1970s and into the 1980s were shot with spring-piston guns, often of the opposing-piston recoil-eliminating type.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Beginning in the 1980s, guns powered by compressed/liquefied carbon dioxide began to dominate the competition.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Today, the guns used at the highest levels of competition are powered by compressed air.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Some newer generation air guns incorporate a gas spring (commonly referred to as a *gas piston*, *gas ram*, *gas strut* or *nitro piston*) instead of a mechanical spring.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] The spring itself is essentially a stand-alone enclosed piston pump without outlets and with pressurized air or inert gas (such as nitrogen) held tightly sealed within the cylinder.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] When the gun is cocked, the gas inside the cylinder gets further compressed by the piston, stores potential energy and acts as a pneumatic accumulator.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Gas spring units require higher precision to manufacture since they require a low-friction sliding seal that can withstand the high pressures within when cocked.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Gas springs perform more reliably in cold climates than coil springs, because metallic coil springs need to be coated with lubricating grease which often thickens in low temperatures causing the gun to "freeze up".
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Gas springs also have less lateral and longitudinal vibrations than coil springs, hence are usually less "hold-sensitive", making it easier to achieve consistent shot groupings.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Pneumatic airguns propel the projectiles by utilizing the pneumatic potential energy within compressed air, which is pressurized beforehand and stored inside the gun, and then released through valves during shooting.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Single-stroke and multi-stroke pump guns utilize an on-board hand pump to pressurize air in an internal reservoir tank, while pre-charged pneumatic guns' reservoirs are filled from an external source using either a high-pressure stand pump or by decanting air from a larger diving cylinder.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Because of the need for cylinders or charging systems, PCP guns have higher initial costs but much lower operating costs when compared to CO2 rifles, and have superior performance over ordinary pump guns.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Having no significant movement of heavy mechanical parts during the discharge cycle, PCP airgun designs produce lower recoil, and can shoot as many as 100 shots per charge depending on the tank/reservoir size.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] The ready supply of air has allowed the development of semi- and fully automatic air guns.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] PCP guns are very popular in Europe because of their accuracy and ease of use.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] They are widely utilized in ISSF 10 meter air pistol and rifle shooting events and the sport of Field Target shooting, and are usually fitted with telescopic sights.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Early stand pump designs encountered problems of fatigue (both human and mechanical), temperature warping, and condensation – none of which are beneficial to accurate shooting or the airguns' longevity.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Modern stand pumps have multi-stage chambers and built-in air filtration systems and have overcome many of these problems.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Using scuba-quality air decanted from a diving cylinder provides consistently clean, dry, high-pressure air.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] During the typical PCP's discharge cycle, the hammer of the rifle is released by the sear to strike the bash valve.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] The hammer may move rearwards or forwards, unlike firearms where the hammer almost always moves forward.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] The valve is held closed by a spring and the pressure of the air in the reservoir.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] The pressure of the spring is constant, and the pressure of the air released (which is also known as the *working pressure*) decreases with each successive shot.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] As a result, when the reservoir pressure is high, the valve opens less fully and closes faster than when the reservoir pressure is lower, resulting in a similar total volume of air flowing past the valve with each shot.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] This results in a degree of partial self-regulation that gives a greater consistency of velocity from shot to shot, which corresponds to the middle "plateau" phase of the gun's shot-to-shot muzzle velocity profile (also known as the *power curve* ).
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Well-designed PCP will display good shot-to-shot consistency over a long period, as the air reservoir is being depleted.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Other PCP rifles and pistols are regulated, i.e. the firing valve operates within a secondary chamber separated from the main air reservoir by the regulator body.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] The regulator maintains the pressure within this secondary chamber at a set pressure (lower than the main reservoir's) until the main reservoir's pressure drops to the point where it can no longer do so.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] As a result, shot-to-shot consistency is maintained for longer than in an unregulated rifle, and the gun can also output more shots due to reduced waste of reservoir pressure.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] CO2 guns are popular for training, as the guns and ammunition are inexpensive, relatively safe to use, and no specialized facilities are needed for safety.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] In addition, they can be purchased and owned in areas where firearms possession is either strictly controlled or banned outright.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Most CO2 powered guns are relatively inexpensive, and there are a few precision target guns available that use CO2.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] The high-pressure air (HPA) system, or *N2*, was originally developed for paintball markers as a replacement for CO2 cartridges, and uses powerlet interface-compatible diving cylinders filled with either pure nitrogen or compressed air (which is 78% nitrogen).
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Because nitrogen is more inert than CO2, it remains in the gaseous state longer when compressed; when it expands, it cools due to the Joule-Thomson effect, but at a far lower rate than liquid CO2 because there is no change in state from liquid to gas.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] This thermostability reduces the variation in output pressure associated with rapid successions of firing cycles, improving accuracy and reliability in extreme climates.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] However, because compressed air is stored at higher pressures (up to 34 MPa or 4,900 psi) than liquid CO2 (stored at around 8 MPa or 1,200 psi), HPA cylinders are more expensive.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Cylinders smaller than 1.1 L (67 cu in) may not even last as long as a standard CO2 cartridge when subjected to frequent use.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] It is also possible to power an HPA-compatible gun directly from a plug-in air compressor without using a gas cylinder, though this type of setup is rare.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Each air cartridge is essentially a self-contained gas reservoir housed inside a cartridge case (usually in the size of a .38 Special), with an internal bash valve designed to release the content when the base of the cartridge is struck.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Prior to shooting, each cartridge is pre-filled with sufficient compressed air for one shot (typically via a multi-stroke hand pump) and has a .177/.22 caliber pellet pre-seated to its front slot, and the entire cartridge is then inserted into a chamber in the gun barrel.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] When shooting, the hammer hits the rear of the air cartridge, mimicking the function of a centerfire ammunition.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] This allows the airgun to be constructed and operated in similar fashions to genuine firearms.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] It also allows for higher shot consistency because each cartridge can be easily filled to an identical air charge, essentially removing the "power curve" of conventional PCP guns and bypassing any need for regulators.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] It also simplifies the magazine feed design and eliminates the risk of deforming the projectiles when the action seats each pellet, as the soft lead pellet is protected from contact with the action probe by the harder cartridge casing.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] The air cartridge system, both in the rifle and revolver forms, was at the peak of its popularity throughout the 1990s.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] The popularity of the Brocock range was such that, by 2002, estimates put the number of air cartridge guns in circulation around 70,000-80,000.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] However, a small number of incidents relating to the alleged illegal conversion of (mainly) Brococks to allow them to discharge live ammunition sparked a media frenzy.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] After the UK government implemented the Anti-social Behaviour Act 2003 in January 2004, it became illegal to possess such airguns without a firearm certificate in the United Kingdom.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Brocock subsequently ceased production of all air cartridge systems and turned to focus primarily on PCP airguns.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] The most popular ammunition used in rifled air guns is made of lead, a heavy metal.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Lead is highly poisonous (whether inhaled or swallowed), affecting almost every organ and system in the human body.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] For this reason, lead-free pellets are becoming increasingly popular, and are available in all major shapes and styles, just like traditional lead pellets.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] In flight, the skirt has greater drag-to-weight ratio than the head and exerts a rearward pull behind the center of mass, similar to that of a shuttlecock.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] This produces a phenomenon known as *drag stabilization*, which helps to counteract yawing and maintain a consistent flight path.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] However, the diabolo shape also means that the overall pellet will have poor ballistic coefficient and tends to lose energy quickly and be more unstable especially in the transonic region (272–408 m/s ~ 893–1340 ft/s).
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Diabolo pellets are conventionally made from lead, but are widely available in non-lead alternatives, such as tin, or a combination of materials such as steel or gold alloys with polymer tips.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] A variety of lead-free pellets are offered by all major pellet manufacturers, including H&N Sport, RWS, JSB, Gamo, and others.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Since lead is very dense, it has a higher ballistic coefficient than lightweight alternatives such as tin, copper, or plastic.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] At the present time, the airgun industry does not mass-produce dense alternatives to lead with a high ballistic coefficient for long-range shooting.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Some manufacturers also have recently introduced the more cylindro-conoidal-shaped "slug" pellets for the more powerful modern PCP air rifles.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Appropriately sized bullets cast from firearm bullet molds can be used in big bore air rifles.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Caution should be used when handling lead projectiles or preparing animals for food, as lead fragments can be easily missed inside the meat.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Lead-free slugs in airgun calibers are gradually being developed and becoming available for purchase from manufacturers such as Zan Projectiles, due in part to regulations on hunting with lead projectiles in many areas.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] The BB shot was once the most common airgun ammunition in the US, thanks to the popularity of Daisy's line of BB airguns.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] A BB is a small metallic ball in 4.5 mm/.177" diameter, typically made of steel (with a copper or zinc coating) or lead.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Originally called the "round shot", the contemporary name came from the "BB"- size lead birdshot used in shotgun shells, which the first BB gun invented in 1886 was designed to shoot.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Steel BBs can be acceptably accurate at short distances when fired from properly designed BB guns with smoothbore barrels.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Lead #3 buckshot pellets can be used in .25" caliber airguns as if they were large BBs.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Therefore, steel BBs lack the spin stabilization required for long-range accuracy, and usage in any but the cheapest rifled guns is discouraged.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] The softer lead BBs, however, can be used in rifled barrels.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Typically BBs are used for indoor practice, casual outdoor plinking, training children, or to save money, as they are significantly cheaper than pellets.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Replica CO2 pistols allow people to train with a BB gun, saving a lot of money to centerfire firearm cartridges.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Care should be exercised to avoid ricochet, and safety glasses are recommended.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Recently, manufacturers have created frangible BBs, which break apart and do not ricochet, reducing the hazards associated with BB guns.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Some shotgunners use sightless BB rifles to train in instinctive shooting.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Similar guns were also used briefly by the United States Army in a Vietnam-era instinctive shooting program called "Quick Kill".
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] In the 18th and 19th centuries, air gun darts were popular, largely because they could be reused.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Although less popular now, several different types of darts are made to be used in air guns, but it is not recommended that darts be used in air guns with rifled bores or in spring-powered air guns.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Air guns that shoot darts are sometimes called *dart guns*, and *tranquilizer guns* if the darts used are loaded with anesthetic (tranquilizer) compounds.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Some modern air guns are designed to discharge arrows and are called *arrow guns* or sometimes *airbows*.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] These arrows are designed with a hollow shaft that is open in the rear where the nock would normally be.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] When loaded, the hollow arrow shaft is slid rearwards over a barrel whose external diameter is only fractionally smaller than the shaft's interior diameter, providing a close-enough fitting that minimizes rattling and gives a reasonable enveloping seal without causing too much friction.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] During shooting, the trigger releases high-pressure air from the barrel to the front portion of the hollow arrow shaft, pushing the arrow forward.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Such air guns can shoot arrows at launch velocities rivalling or even exceeding high-end crossbows, while retaining consistency of precision unaffected by archer's paradox, but they are also more expensive to set up and maintain.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] The modern pentathlon has since 2009 included a laser-run event that replaced the traditional cross country run of 3,200 metres and timed air-pistol shoot.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] The competitors run 4 laps of 800 m combined with 4 rounds of firing.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] The pistols used are modified air pistols that fire an eye-safe laser beam towards a target at the same time as a discharge of air.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] This has made the organisation of the events easier from a safety point of view and allows competitors to travel more easily with their weapons.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Airsoft pellets are plastic BBs shot from airsoft guns.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Larger caliber air rifles suitable for hunting large animals are offered by major manufacturers.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Custom air guns are available in even larger calibers such as 20 mm (0.79") or .87 (22.1 mm).
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] While in some countries air guns are not subject to any specific regulation, in most, there are laws which differ widely.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Each jurisdiction has its definition of an air gun.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Regulations may vary for weapons of different bore, muzzle energy, velocity, or ammunition material.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Guns designed to fire metal pellets are often more tightly controlled than airsoft weapons.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] There may be a minimum age for possession, and sales of both air guns and ammunition may be restricted.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] Some areas require permits and background checks similar to those required for propellant type firearms.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] While historical air guns have been made specifically for warfare, modern air guns can also be deadly.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] In medical literature, modern air guns have been noted as a cause of death.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] This has been the case for guns of caliber .177 and .22 that are within the legal muzzle energy of air guns in the United Kingdom.
[src:bb-gun/air-gun] For reason of safety and security a rule of use of the safety flag has been strictly mentioned by ISSF for the 10m air pistol and rifle shooting sports events.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Depending on the mechanism for pellet propulsion, airsoft guns fall into two broad groups just like conventional airguns.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] One group is spring-piston guns, which utilize elastic energy of a coil spring to propel piston air pump that is either manually cocked (i.e.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] "spring guns", commonly referred to as "*springers*", and are the simplest, cheapest and generally of low quality); or automatically cycled by a battery-powered electric motor gearbox (i.e.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] "gas guns"), which operate by bash valve-controlled pressure release of prefilled bottled gas such as compressed propane mixed with silicone oil (commonly known as "Green Gas") or CO2 canisters (Powerlets.).
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Pneumatic guns can be cycled either manually by hand-pulling back the bolt or slide, which loads the subsequent shot; or automatically by having the released propellant gas also pushing back the action (i.e.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Airsoft guns are often designed to aesthetically resemble real firearms, which provides more realism but also makes it difficult to distinguish them from actual lethal weapons.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Airsoft in the past was used almost solely for recreational purposes, but in 2012, gas blowback (GBB) airsoft technology became adopted by US federal and state institutions as an affordable and reliable tactical training tool for close quarters battles.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] In 2018, the United States Coast Guard officially adopted SIG-branded P229 airsoft pistol for training.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Airsoft guns also allow basic and advanced shooter training in a safer environment by reducing the risks of accidental injury or death from a negligent discharge.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] There are clubs, teams, and even athletic associations devoted to airsoft events around the world.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Europe is home to some of the largest events, with skirmishes of over 2,000 people participating.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] In North America, in 2012 alone, Fulda Gap Airsoft Game in Taylorsville, North Carolina had over 1,100 participants, and Operation Lion Claws Military Simulation Series (OLCMSS) had 800 people attend at George Air Force Base in Victorville, California.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] American Mil-sim, Black Sheep, and Ballahack also host large games.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Events may include a variety of equipment ranging from small arms to armored vehicles.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] In many countries, every airsoft gun owner and active enthusiast must be affiliated with an accredited airsoft association or federation.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Most airsoft players host games at a registered field where combat situations are simulated using airsoft weaponry like replica pistols, submachine guns, carbines/assault rifles, DMRs/sniper rifles, light machine guns, grenades and landmines.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Great variety and profusion of militaria is usually used.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Historical reenactment of famous war situations is another favorite of many airsoft players and clubs.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] In addition, a number of companies such as Systema Engineering and Celsius Technology manufacture ultra-realistic high-velocity airsoft rifles designed specifically for the police and military for non-lethal training purposes.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] People today may also use airsoft guns as props for film making, particularly after the *Rust* shooting incident.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] An Airsoft Two-Tone Gun is an Airsoft replica which has been sprayed over 51% a bright, non military colour, so that it complies with the Violent Crimes Reduction Act (VCRA, 2006), allowing anyone to buy a replica without having to prove that they have a legitimate use for it.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Spring guns are generally inexpensive (except the high-power sniper rifles and shotguns), and may not last long (depending on the build quality) due to the tension exerted on the gun parts by the recoiling of a powerful spring.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] However, many spring guns can be modified and upgraded to last longer and shoot more powerfully.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Low-end spring guns tend to be much cheaper than their electric equivalents due to their lack of electrical components (electric motor/actuator, spring-gearbox assembly, battery and battery charger).
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] These guns are less common in competitions because their rate-of-fire is a disadvantage against automatic guns in close combat, and they do not provide enough accuracy and power for long-range use.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] There are some exceptions, however, as higher-end spring-powered airsoft rifles can be quite expensive; these guns are typically suited for "marksman" applications in airsoft matches and provide competitive muzzle velocities.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Additionally, pump shotguns are sometimes used for both short and long range engagements.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] In colder weather, spring pistols are more reliable than gas-powered pistols and even the batteries on automatic electric pistols (AEPs) both of which can be adversely affected by extremely low temperatures.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] This represents one of the major advantages of spring airsoft gun, as it can be fired in practically any situation without relying on batteries or bottled gas.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] This independence from external power sources causes some players to favor spring-powered guns.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Spring guns are also less susceptible to the effects of water, where a battery-powered gun could short-circuit and malfunction when wet.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Because of their low price, availability, and simplicity, spring guns tend to act as training guns for new players.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] In the UK, they are affectionately known as "springers" and were often a player's introduction to the sport due to the entry-level cost in comparison to AEG and GBB weapons.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Some veteran airsoft players still rely on sniper rifle and shotgun-type spring guns as a primary weapon due to reliability, high power, accuracy, low noise, and ease of repair compared to AEGs and GBB guns.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Selective fire options among automatic, 3-round burst and semi-automatic operations are all possible, which gives these guns the popular name "**automatic electric guns**", or **AEGs**.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] They are the most commonly used and widely available type of airsoft gun.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] AEGs were developed in Japan and the Japanese company Tokyo Marui is credited with creating the original gearbox system.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] In a Tokyo Marui AEG, the motor drives a train of three gears mounted inside a gearbox, which then loads a pump piston against a spring.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Once the spring is released, it pushes the piston plunger forward through the pump cylinder to propel a pellet resting within the chamber forward through the barrel and out of the muzzle.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Many manufacturers have now more or less replicated this basic model, adding reinforced parts or minor improvements.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] The electric airsoft guns were powered primarily by nickel-metal hydride (NiMH) batteries with varying voltages and milliampere-hour ratings.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] The most common battery is an 8.4 V large battery pack, with a capacity between 2200 and 5000 mAh.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Also available are "mini" and "stick" batteries, which generally have 900 ~ 1600 mAh capacities.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Voltages for NiMH batteries range from 7.2 V to 12 V.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] The usual rule of thumb is that the higher the mAh rating, the longer the battery lasts; the higher the voltage, the higher the rate of fire.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] The most common AEGs are the AR-15 series (such as M16 rifle and M4 carbine, sometimes referred to as the ArmaLite or Colt series), the H&K MP5 series, and the AK or Kalashnikov series.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Also increasingly popular is the H&K G36 and, more recently, the FN P90 and H&K MP7.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Subsequently, numerous parts for repairs and modifications are commonly available for these rifles.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Some airsoft guns are called *low-powered electric guns* (LPEGs) to distinguish them from the original, more expensive and more powerful AEGs even though their mechanical/electrical design and operation is similar.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] MPEGs are the middle ground between LPEGs and AEGs.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Some companies, like UTG with their popular MP5 and AK-47 models, have improved their quality to such an extent that some models are now considered more affordable AEGs.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Electric blowbacks, also known as EBBs, are typically available at lower prices than their battery-powered counterparts.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] They generally run on AAA or AA batteries.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Most models utilizing this system are rifles.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] EBBs simulate the blowback action of a real pistol or rifle.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Essentially an AEG in design, EBBs are just as powerful.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] However, a drawback to having the realistic recoil feature is the tendency of the battery to quickly deplete.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Additionally, blowbacks can cause extra stress on the gear box which may result in a shorter life span.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Automatic electric pistols, abbreviated AEPs, were first introduced by Tokyo Marui in 2005 with their Glock 18C (followed later by a Beretta 93R model).
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] They were the first handguns to incorporate an electrically powered system that is capable of fully automatic operation.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] In cold weather, AEPs are often considered better sidearms than gas powered pistols, because batteries are not as badly affected by frigid weather.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Gases like CO2 and green gas are stored in liquid form and require heat in order to vaporize.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] A gas pistol at 10 °F (−12 °C) will usually only get one to two usable shots from a full magazine, and even will be at reduced power because of the lowered pressure of the gas.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Because the AEP gearbox and battery are smaller, the velocity of AEP BBs (usually between 200 and 280 ft/s (85.3 m/s)) is relatively slow by the standards of airsoft simulations, rendering them useful only for close-range simulation.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] However, the advanced hop up units on these new guns tend to compensate for the low power and can produce an effective range comparable to those of an AEG.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] CYMA has made a clone Glock 18C, which is a lower priced alternative.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] An AEP differs from electric blow-backs because the AEP has a fixed slide (in which there is no external movement of the slide during operation), while an EBB simulates the "blow back" action in the slide experienced in a real pistol or Gas Blow Back (GBB).
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] An AEP, however, has much more power and accuracy.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] One of the newer AEP-styled guns is the Marui replica of the Heckler & Koch MP7.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] It is considerably larger than either of the other guns, and can be upgraded to a much higher power through the use of an external battery, but uses the same system as the AEP, so the classification is ambiguous.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] It is slightly more powerful than the others and is a suitable choice for CQB (Close Quarter Battle) games due to its small size and decent barrel- to gun-length ratio.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Some semi-automatic pistols can be modified to be automatic pistols.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] To make them more effective, they use rechargeable batteries supplied with the gun, which can be replaced with a larger battery to increase their ROF.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Due to restrictions on size, either the electric motor or batteries have to occupy space in the hand grip, reducing the available space for a magazine.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Because of this, most AEPs do not use a full size magazine found in most gas powered pistols.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] They are typically constructed almost entirely of plastic and have a light, toy-like feeling to them.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Gas-powered airsoft guns use the pneumatic potential energy stored within compressed gas to drive the shooting mechanism, and thus operate according to an entirely different design principle to spring- or electrically powered airsoft guns.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] The most common type seen is the gas blowback (GBB) guns.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] These gas guns use an internal canister (usually within the magazine) that upon trigger-pull releases the prefilled bottled gas via a series of valves to propel the pellet and generate a blowback, which simulates recoil and cyclically loads the next shot.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] They are capable of both automatic and semi-automatic operation.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] The most common gases used are "green gas" and propane which requires an adaptor.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] HFC-134a is also commonly used, particularly with pistols which have plastic sliders due to the lower pressure giving a smaller chance of damage to the weaker slide.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Less commonly used gases include "red gas" (which is actually HCFC-22), CO2 and nitrogen/high-pressure air.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] However, it is unlawful to use HCFC-22 as a propellant in the US, as it is a Class II ozone-depleting substance and its use as an aerosol propellant has been banned since January 1994 under section 610(d) of Clean Air Act.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Red gas is usually avoided unless the airsoft gun has undergone modification, as its relatively high critical pressure can cause damage to the airsoft gun, such as breakage of the slide or bolt.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] CO2, nitrogen, and high pressure air are less common because they need to be stored at higher pressures than "green gas" or HFC-134a.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] The first ever gas powered airsoft guns were commonly referred to as "classic" guns, owing to their age.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] R-12 was a commonly used refrigerant for car air conditioning and refrigerators, and is considered a highly potent ozone-depleting substance and listed as a Class I Ozone Depleting Substance by the US EPA.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Its use as a general purpose aerosol propellant has been banned by the US EPA since March 1978 under 43 FR 11301 for use in aerosol use with a very few exceptions.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Its use is also banned in many countries under United Nations treaties.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] On December 31, 2008, the use of CFCs for medical inhalers was banned.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Later users modified these old guns to be powered by regulated CO2 canisters or nitrogen/high pressure air bottles to increase power and consistency.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] However, these guns have largely been superseded by the newer and more versatile AEGs, or automatic electric guns.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] One of the reasons for this is because the most commonly available propellant, R-12, is costly.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Additionally, at high flow rates, liquid propellants tend to cool down, eventually freezing.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] As cooldown progresses, the rate of fire gradually decreases until the gun ceases operation.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] The user would then be forced to wait for the propellant to warm up again.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] CO2 is not affected as badly by this tendency, and nitrogen/high pressure air is immune to it.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Furthermore, if liquid propellant is introduced into the gun's mechanism, rubber parts can freeze and eventually damage the gun.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] However, it is unlikely for this to occur since once the gas is released from the containing cylinder it instantly turns back into its gaseous state, and expands rapidly.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] It is doubtful whether the retained pressure behind the BB before it begins to accelerate down the barrel is enough to keep the gas in a liquid form.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Also, any gun that is expected to be exposed to the intense cold of de-pressurizing gas should have materials that can handle it.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Gas power tends to be used in airsoft pistols where size constraints make electric-powered mechanisms impractical.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Other instances where gas is favored are where adjustable velocities are required or where a blowback feature is desired.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] A blowback feature is a mechanism which cycles a slide or bolt to better simulate a real firearm's operation.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Because of the mechanical complexities involved with distributing and regulating gas, these guns have largely given way to electric guns for less specialized applications, however, they still remain favorable amongst most airsofters.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] They are not just limited to pistols; submachine guns, sniper rifles and assault rifles commonly use gas mechanisms.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Whilst the submachine gun replicas typically feature a blowback mechanism similar to the pistol replicas, sniper rifle replicas usually omit the blowback mechanism in favor of reduced recoil and increased muzzle velocity.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Along with using gas to power guns, it is also applied for use in replica grenades.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] These grenades are either projectiles, fired from a grenade launcher such as the M203 or GP-25, or throwable.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] The shells work on the system of an internal piston, filled with gas.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Either a series of BB's or in some cases a rubber or soft foam head is seated in or on top of the shell.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] When the pressure is released the projectile(s) are shot from the launcher sent downrange.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] In the case of the throwable grenades, inside the grenade there is a similar piston to the one used in the shells, but is on a literal "timer" that allows the user to clear the area of effect.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] BBs or powder acts as the projectile in the case of these grenades.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Currently both types of grenades are not very common, mostly because grenade launchers are quite expensive and the throwable grenades are not very reliable.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] High pressure air (HPA) systems are a type of pneumatic airsoft weapon that use externally supplied high pressure air instead of internal gas canisters like the majority of gas-operated airsoft guns.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] They work by using a separate high-pressure air tank that is connected to the airsoft gun with a hose, which is connected with a pneumatic motor inside the gun (called an "engine") at where the gearbox would be in a normal electric airsoft gun.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] The engine is powered by a fire control unit that can adjust to the desired rates of fire as well as the dwell that determines how much air is released with each individual shot.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Airsoft gun manufacturer Systema Engineering (PTW) developed a line of airsoft guns and accessories intended for military and law enforcement training.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] These airsoft guns are made of aircraft-grade aluminium combined with stainless steel parts that gives strength, stability, weather protection, and easy maintenance.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] These training weapons offer a more realistic display of military weapons.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Unfortunately they have been plagued by reliability problems and parts availability.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] They have also had models banned from the US for being capable of being converted into real firearms.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Two manufactures, King Arms and KWA, came out with ATF-approved gas blowback AR-15 replicas that allowed for correct weapons tear down, manipulation and function that were designed for military use, but were also legal for US citizens to own.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] The King Arms model required upgrade parts out of the parts to give it reliability, though the KWA was plagued by a weak hop-up system, but otherwise reliable.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Airsoft guns shoot plastic pellets at velocities from 30 m/s (98 ft/s) for a low-end spring pistol, to 200 m/s (660 ft/s) for heavily upgraded customized sniper rifles.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Most non-upgraded AEGs are in the middle, producing velocities from 90 m/s (300 ft/s) to 120 m/s (390 ft/s).
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] The internal components of most guns can be upgraded which can increase the pellet velocity significantly.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Using heavier pellets (.25 g, .3 g, etc.) will significantly reduce the gun's muzzle velocity, but can increase accuracy at range and reduce susceptibility to wind drift.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Lighter pellets have less kinetic energy than their heavier pellets, despite their higher exit velocity.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Decreasing the pellet's weight does not generally increase its range.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] A common upgrade done by players is in the "hop-up" system, featured in most mid- to high-end AEGs, as well as gas guns and spring sniper rifles.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] In this system, the wall of a rubber tube, called a bucking, is forced into the upper path of the pellet right before it begins flying down the inner barrel.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] This contact imparts backspin, which in turn gives the pellet a Magnus lift to maintain a flatter trajectory for a longer period of time.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] This is adjusted by screws or gears that cause the bucking to only show a small or large presence in the barrel.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Different degrees of firmness of the rubber are considered when a hop-up is being upgraded.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Airsoft is safe when played with proper protective gear.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Most airsoft guns on the market are usually below 350 ft/s (110 m/s), but projectiles expelled from any type of airsoft gun can travel as slow as 65 ft/s (20 m/s) to more than 700 ft/s (210 m/s) and are capable of breaking skin at 350–400 ft/s (110–120 m/s).
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] For example, skirmish play in the United Kingdom has a maximum of 350 ft/s, with some airsoft locations having a limit as low as 290 ft/s.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] If under 300 ft/s (91 m/s), the hit would have to be within a short range.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Blood can be drawn, but injuries that do occur are predominantly superficial.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Full-seal protective eyewear (goggles or glasses) is widely considered the minimum protection for airsoft players, as the eyes may be injured by any type of impact.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] The least amount of protection a player should seek will meet or exceed ANSI/ISEA Z87.1 standards, which indicates the eyewear is rated for ballistic strikes.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Mesh eyewear has also seen some limited use by players due to low cost and its inability to fog, although it has drawn some criticism for its non-impact rated construction and vulnerability to debris.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Some impacts (particularly at close range with powerful guns) are capable of cracking or damaging teeth.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Dentists have reported broken teeth that require root canal and crowns to repair damage.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] A face mask (like that used for paintball) is recommended to protect eyes and teeth.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Metallic mesh masks and mouth guards have recently seen popular use.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] There are legal issues in airsoft as well as several rules imposed in a game by game basis.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Most indoor airsoft fields only allow up to 350 ft/s (110 m/s), and most outdoor fields begin capping near the 410 ft/s (125 m/s) for rifles and 525 ft/s (160 m/s) for long-range guns such as sniper rifles.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Most outdoor fields also impose a minimum engagement distance for guns firing over a certain range, normally for squad support weapons and sniper rifles.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] In order for an airsoft gun to cause any serious injury, it would have to be well over these limits and in close proximity.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] To even reach such speeds, the gun would have to be highly modified.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] So it is therefore unlikely to cause permanent or serious damage with any stock airsoft gun.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] The use of metallic BBs, or any foreign objects, is very dangerous for the user and other people and property in close vicinity, and may damage the airsoft gun as well.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] However, specially designed and built metallic 6 mm BBs for airsoft guns can be found on the market.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] These metallic BBs should not be used for airsoft play because they can break through goggles and other safety gear.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Plastic BBs can be a mixture of PLA and Plastic causing less damage to persons.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Although airsoft guns in the United States are generally sold with a 6 mm (0.24in.) or longer orange tip on the barrel in order to distinguish them from real firearms, this is not in fact required by federal law.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Full or partial preventive painting of airsoft guns as a legal obligation to avoid confusion of the airsoft replicas with real lethal weapons is in practice in several jurisdictions around the world.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] A common controversy referred to as "pumping" or "roping" is the act of purposely firing 20+ airsoft rounds at one player until they run away or submit in pain.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Popular videos such as *Rip Kid* and *SC Trip 2015* have both documented the act of pumping.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] A CBS News report noted that since from 2014 to 2024, more than 300 people had been shot and killed by police while holding realistic replica guns, of which 19 were minors.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Some airsoft guns can be such accurate replicas that they violate intellectual property laws (specifically those regarding trademarks), most notably some models from Tokyo Marui bearing Colt or Heckler & Koch trademarks that may not be imported into the United States.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Certain companies such as Classic Army or ICS avoid this problem by licensing their replicas from the original manufacturers, such as ArmaLite by license from ActionSportGames or Olympic Arms.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] The airsoft company ActionSportGames has licensed trademark rights from many well-known firearm manufacturers, such as Armalite, Dan Wesson, CZ, Steyr, STI, B&T and Franchi.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Another company who licence the designs of gun companies is Evolution International.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] It has a portfolio of exclusive licenses from ADC Armi Dallera Custom, TangoDown, Z-M Weapons, DSR precision, Lone Star Tactical, and SAR.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] In addition, there have been reports of companies taking action in defense of their intellectual property rights.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Some end users have made attempts to sell their guns, some in the style of Glock pistols, only to find Glock blocking the sale and threatening legal action.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] In addition to these actions, Glock, as well as Heckler & Koch, have blocked the sale, trade and distribution of replicas bearing resemblance to their products.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] Recently, Glock gave the licensing to the Glock name and likeness to Elite Force/Umarex to produce replica models of the real Glock series of firearms.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] In response, SIG Air, SIG Sauer's airgun division, announced on January 17, 2019, that it was introducing its own in-house ProForce airsoft line for professional training, with the initial offerings include the M17 and P229 airsoft pistol.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-gun] SIG Air also announced that "we are rapidly expanding the SIG AIR business, and it is important to us to assume full control to ensure all SIG Air products are of the highest quality", and it would no longer be licensing the "SIG" brand or trademarks for sale by commercial airsoft manufacturers.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Although the majority of pellets bought and used are simple spherical projectiles made of plastic, some of the following special varieties can be used to give a player an advantage, such as higher quality pellets.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Biodegradable pellets are available, and are often required by outdoor fields where sweeping is not an option.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Conventional pellets pollute the environment, as most non-biodegradable pellets have a mineral or petroleum-based center, coated in non-biodegradable plastics, thus ensuring they will stay in the environment for several hundred years if not collected.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Biodegradable pellets are made of various types of resin, often developed for the agricultural industry, and better makes are certified as compostable.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Commonly used plastic resins include polylactic acid or polylactide (PLA) which is based on renewable materials like corn products and a molecular formula of (C3H4O2)n.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] There is a mixture of degradable processes being used, such as soil microbes and photosensitive degradation.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Biodegradable pellets are currently being produced with all the characteristics of the best of the conventional, with homogeneous resin construction.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Most high-quality pellets are available in a non-biodegradable version, as well as a biodegradable version that costs slightly more.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Both bio- and non-biodegradable pellets are popular and widely available.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Glow-in-the-dark pellets, known as *tracer* pellets, can be used in conjunction with a device that "charges" the pellets by flashing them with a burst of light before leaving the barrel so that they remain luminescent in flight for use during nocturnal games/operations.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] This tracer unit is usually hidden from view, often disguised as a suppressor, or is included inside the magazine or hop-up unit.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] There are also biodegradable tracer pellets available.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] This type of pellet is dark-colored so that the opponent has a tougher time spotting the pellets' origin, as the most common pellet color is white, which makes it easy for the opposition to spot the shooter by following the trail of pellets.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Two major problems of this variant of pellet are that there are few high-quality pellets in this color and the shooter has a difficult time seeing their own trail of shots.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Paint-filled pellets are also available, called "paintballs", which are very similar to those used in paintball.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Airsoft models equipped with the hop-up projectile stabilizing system are not able to use these, as the thin shells are liable to break in the barrel, covering the inside with paint.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] These special pellets are also incompatible with airsoft models using mechanized feeding systems, such as high capacity magazines, for the same reason.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] With some companies, the use of paintballs voids the airsoft gun's warranty; paint may get into the mechanical workings of the airsoft gun and damage parts beyond simple maintenance.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] These issues may be fixed by removing the hop-up unit, which can void the warranty, and also switching to a low or mid-capacity magazine with no mechanized feed.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] A specialized pellet coated in a powder or liquid that leaves a small colored mark when it strikes a surface.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] The powder deposits from these pellets are left in any part of the airsoft gun or storage unit that the pellet comes in contact with; build-up over time, without cleaning, can cause malfunctions or damage to moving parts.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Made from (most commonly) 100% silica, the material in these pellets is very evenly distributed, improving flight characteristics.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Some accounts indicate that these pellets are capable of breaking glass and industry-standard protective eyewears.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Due to safety concerns and reports of injuries caused by this type of pellets, it is commonly prohibited in professional airsoft facilities.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Metal pellets are also marketed for use in airsoft guns.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] These pellets are heavier and harder than conventional polymer pellets, and the impact from a metal pellet can injure players.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Safety concerns make metallic pellets suitable only for target shooting.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] The added weight reduces the effect of crosswind on the pellet, imparting more accuracy when fired at longer ranges in outdoor environments where wind would significantly alter the trajectory of traditional pellets.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Many airsoft locations where players can pay to play against others prohibit the use of metallic pellets due to the fact they are more likely to penetrate skin.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Metallic pellets are mostly used in a standard pump-action or carbon dioxide-powered BB guns.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Created from laboratory-grown crystal lattice structures, these pellets are individually machined to precise specifications that ensure uniform weight, dimensions and surface shape.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] This precision and uniformity provides ideal ballistic performance and consistent flight patterns.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] The manufacturing process and materials are much more costly than molded polymer pellets – as a result, ceramic pellets are considerably more expensive than standard airsoft pellets.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Translucent pellets come in many colors.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] They tend to be non-biodegradeable and it can be difficult to find high quality versions compared to their opaque counterparts.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Pellet mass is an important factor when choosing pellets.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] A player's choice of pellet mass is governed by their gaming style (assaulting vs. sniping), the airsoft gun used (internal parts), game venue condition (in/outdoor) and size, and muzzle velocity regulations.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Also, the quality of the individual pellets may influence choice of price-range or manufacturer.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Low-cost pellets are often considered to have such negative characteristics as residual plastic from the moulding process (flash); lower impact resistance and some deviation from perfect spherical shape.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Cheaper pellets are known to shatter when fired, which can cause irreparable damage to the internals of the gun.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Higher cost BBs generally have a smoother finish, are more impact resistant and are perfectly spherical.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] 6 mm is the industrial standard size used in almost all spring, electric and gas airsoft guns.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] A wide variety of pellet masses are also available for different usages.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] 8 mm (0.315 in) pellets are most commonly used in gas-powered airsoft shotguns with high velocities.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] The pellet speed of spring-powered and automatic electric guns is determined in large part by the tension of the gun's main spring.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Muzzle velocity limits are between 90 and 120 m/s (300 and 390 ft/s) for AEGs and 120 to 170 m/s (390–560 ft/s) for single-shot spring sniper rifles.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] For comparison purposes, 3.00 g (46+3⁄10 gr) is the typical mass of a paintball pellet, and 0.2 g (3+9⁄100 gr) is the standard for an airsoft pellet.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] At 3 g mass, a pellet flying at 100 m/s (330 ft/s) has 15 J of kinetic energy, while a 0.20 g has 1 J.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] It is important to distinguish that, in airsoft, the terminal impact energy is very close to the kinetic energy of the pellet because the collision is almost completely elastic.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] On the other hand, in paintball, the pellet fractures upon impact, leading to an inelastic collision with energy loss, and thus the impact energy is smaller than the kinetic energy of the pellet.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Nevertheless, the typical impact energies of the airsoft pellet tend to be much smaller than of the paintball.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] While a pellet's muzzle velocity is important for safety proposes, it will lose velocity during flight due to drag.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] where *v* is the instantaneous velocity of the pellet.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] For typical values of the pellet (*m* = 0.2 g, *v* = 120 m/s, *D* = 6 mm), the drag can be very high ( $576\ \mathrm {m} /\mathrm {s} ^{2}$ ), which means that the velocity decreases quite fast.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] In particular, for typical values and neglecting wind effects or hop-up usage, a straight shot from a height of 1.8 m (5.9 ft) has a range of 34 m (37 yd).
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] On ground hit, the impact energy of the pellet is 0.1 J.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] However, the same shot at close quarters (e.g.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] 5 m distance) has an impact energy of 1 J (see figure).
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Airsoft pellets travelling with sufficient velocity can leave small superficial wounds when hitting exposed skin.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] While this can be painful, these wounds are typically closed contusions and heal quickly without needing any medical attention.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] However, pellets can cause more serious damage to the more vulnerable parts of the body, such as the eyes and ears.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Lower protective face masks are recommended during airsoft matches to shield players' nose, mouth, teeth and ears, and goggles or other protective eyewear are mandatory for eye protection.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] where *m* is the mass of a spherical bullet, in grams.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Penetration is defined here as entering the skin to a depth of more than half of the spherical pellet's diameter.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Accordingly, a typical 0.20 g airsoft pellet will penetrate the skin at 136.7 m/s (448 ft/s).
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Because many high-end AEGs, spring- and gas-powered airsoft guns can achieve such velocity at close ranges, many airsoft venues set strict limits on the maximum muzzle velocities allowed on the field, requiring each player to undergo a chronograph test prior to participating in a game.
[src:bb-gun/airsoft-pellet] Some venues even have restrictions on minimal engagement distances, where shooting at opponents nearer than a set distance is prohibited, and a "bang bang" rule (players imitate firing by shouting "bang bang" instead of really firing the weapon) is often implemented.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] An **anti-personnel mine** or **anti-personnel landmine** (**APL** or **APERS**) is a form of mine designed for use against humans, as opposed to an anti-tank mine, which target vehicles.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] APLs are classified into **blast mines** and **fragmentation mines**; the latter may or may not be a bounding mine.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] APLs are often designed to injure and maim, not kill, their victims to overwhelm the logistical (mostly medical) support system of enemy forces that encounter them.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] Some types of APLs can also damage the tracks on armoured vehicles or the tires of wheeled vehicles.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] The International Campaign to Ban Landmines has sought to ban mines and destroy stockpile.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] For this purpose, it introduced in 1997 the Ottawa Treaty, which has not yet been accepted by over 30 states and has not guaranteed the protection of citizens against APLs planted by non-state armed groups.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] Anti-personnel mines are used in a similar manner to anti-tank mines, in static "mine fields" along national borders or in defense of strategic positions as described in greater detail in the land mine article.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] What makes them different from most anti-tank mines, however, is their smaller size, which enables large numbers to be simultaneously deployed over a large area.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] This process can be done manually, via dispensers on land vehicles, or from helicopters or aircraft.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] Alternatively, they can be dispensed by cargo-carrying artillery shells.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] Typically, anti-personnel blast mines are triggered when the victim steps on them.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] Their primary purpose is to blow the victim's foot or leg off, disabling them.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] Injuring, rather than killing, the victim is viewed as preferable to increase the logistical (evacuation, medical) burden on the opposing force.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] When a person steps on a blast mine and activates it, the mine's main charge detonates, creating a blast shock wave consisting of hot gases travelling at extremely high velocity.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] The shock wave sends a huge compressive force upwards, ejecting the mine casing and any soil covering the mine along with it.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] When the blast wave hits the surface, it quickly transfers the force into the subject's footwear and foot.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] This results in a massive compression force being applied.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] In most cases, the victim's foot is blown off by the blast wave.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] The resulting injuries to a human body depend on the size of the mine's main charge, the depth, type of soil it was laid in and how the victim contacted it, e.g. stepping on the mine, using all or part of the foot.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] Different types of soil will result in different amounts of energy being transferred upward into the subject's foot, with saturated "clay-like" soil transferring the most.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] Larger main charges result in a release of significantly more energy, driving the blast wave further up a target's foot and leg and causing greater injury, in some cases even described as severe as traumatic amputation of the leg up to the knee.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] Secondary injuries from a blast mine are often caused by the material that has been torn loose by the mine's explosion.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] This consists of the soil and stones that were on top of the mine, parts of the victim's footwear and the small bones in the victim's foot.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] This debris creates wounds typical of similar secondary blast effects or fragmentation.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] Special footwear, including combat boots or so-called "blast boots", is only moderately protective against the destructive effects of blast mines, and the loss of a foot is a typical outcome.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] Blast mines have little effect on armoured vehicles, but can damage a wheeled vehicle if it runs directly over the mine.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] Small blast mines will severely damage a tire, rendering it irreparable while some types could also damage adjacent running gear.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] The mine casing houses the components of the mine and protects it from its environment.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] Early mines, such as the ones used in the World War II era, had casings made of steel or aluminium.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] However, by the middle of the conflict, the British Army was using the first, practical, portable metal detector – the Polish mine detector.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] The Germans responded with mines that had a wooden or glass casing to make detection harder.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] Wooden mines had been used by the Soviets in 1939, before the appearance of metal detectors, to save steel.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] Some, like the PP Mi-D mine, continued to be used into the 1980s as they were easy to make and hard to detect.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] Wood has the disadvantage of rotting and splitting, rendering the mine non-functional after a comparatively short time in the ground (or the advantage, in that the mine can be considered self-disabling, and will be less likely to cause unintended injuries years later).
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] Mines manufactured after the 1950s generally use plastic casings to hinder detection by electronic mine detectors.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] Some, referred to as minimum metal mines, are constructed with as little metal as possible – often around 1 gram (0.035 oz) – to make them difficult to detect.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] Mines containing absolutely no metal have been produced, but are uncommon.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] By its nature, a mine without any metal components in it cannot be found using a metal detector.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] The fuze mechanism is designed to set off the detonator, either by striking it with a spring-loaded firing pin, compressing a friction sensitive pyrotechnic composition, or by passing an electric charge through it.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] Most mines employ a spring-loaded striker that hits a stab detonator when activated by the victim.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] Typically, the detonator contains a tiny pellet of lead azide.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] The fuze is the most complicated component in any mine, although the amount of effort required to design and manufacture a simple fuze mechanism is quite low, similar to the retraction mechanism in a ballpoint pen.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] More sophisticated examples, such as the Italian SB-33 mine, have a fuze mechanism that detonates the mine if subject to gradual, steady pressure, but locks the fuze if subject to a sudden shock.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] This defeats one of the main methods of clearing a path through a minefield – detonating the mines with explosive devices, such as mine-clearing line charges.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] The booster charge is a highly sensitive explosive that will activate easily when subjected to the shock of the detonator.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] Typically, a pea-sized pellet of RDX is used.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] The purpose of the booster is to amplify the shock of the detonator and initiate the main explosive charge.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] The main charge consists of a stable explosive that is detonated by the booster charge.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] This is necessary, because making a mine entirely out of a highly sensitive detonator or booster explosive would be more expensive, and make the device more sensitive and thereby susceptible to accidental detonation.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] In most AP blast mines TNT, Composition B or phlegmatized RDX are used.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] On a US M14 mine, 29 grams of tetryl is used, while 240 grams of TNT is used in a Russian PMN mine.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] Anti-personnel blast mines are the most common type and are typically deployed on the surface (hidden by leaves or rocks) or buried under soil at a depth of 10–15 cm.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] They are activated by pressure, i.e. when the victim steps on them, but it could also be a vehicle driving over them.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] They were designed for use as area denial weapons.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] Weapons of this type are supposed to deny opposing military forces access to a specific area.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] While blast mines are designed to cause severe injury to one person, fragmentation mines (such as the World War II era German S-mine) are designed to project fragments across a wide area, causing fragmentation wounds to nearby personnel.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] Fragmentation mines are generally much larger and heavier than blast mines, and contain a large amount (often several kilograms) of ferrous metal.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] As such, they are easy to detect if the environment is not too heavily contaminated with iron.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] These mines are deemed to be more efficient than purely "blast effect" mines, because the shrapnel covers a greater area, potentially injuring more combatants.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] The shrapnel from these mines can even disable some armoured vehicles, by puncturing their tires and—in the case of soft-skinned vehicles—also penetrating the skin and damaging internal components or injuring personnel.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] Because fragmentation mines generally contain a much larger charge than blast mines, they can cause severe damage to an unarmoured vehicle which runs directly over one.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] These mines (such as the Russian POMZ) are entirely above ground, having a fragmenting warhead mounted on a stake at a suitable height, concealed by vegetation or rubbish and triggered by one or more tripwires.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] Bounding mines have a small lifting charge that, when activated, launches the main body of the mine out of the ground before it detonates at around chest height.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] This produces a more lethal spray of shrapnel over a larger area.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] One such mine – the US M16 mine – can cause injuries up to 200 metres (660 ft) away.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] The steel shrapnel makes bounding mines easy to detect, so they may be surrounded by minimum metal mines to make mine clearance harder.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] Directional fragmentation weapons (such as the M18 Claymore) differ from other types in that they are designed to direct their fragments only in a limited arc.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] They are placed so that the blast will be directed at the target area and away from friendly forces.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] This design also allows forces to protect themselves by placing these types of mines near their own positions, but facing the enemy.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] They are triggered in a conventional manner with either tripwire or command detonation.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] They are generally referred to as *claymore mines* from the US mine of this type.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] In the conflicts of the 21st century, anti-personnel improvised explosive devices (IED) have replaced conventional or military landmines as the source of injury to dismounted (pedestrian) soldiers and civilians.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] These injuries were recently reported in BMJ Open to be far worse than landmines, resulting in multiple limb amputations and lower body mutilation.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] This combination of injuries has been given the name "Dismounted Complex Blast Injury" and is thought to be the worst survivable injury ever seen in war.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] During World War II, flame mines known as the flame fougasse were produced by the British during the invasion crisis of 1940.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] Later, the Soviets produced a flame-mine, called the FOG-1.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] This was copied by the Germans to produce the Abwehrflammenwerfer 42, these devices were effectively disposable, trip-wire triggered flamethrowers.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] They were made by Britain, the US and the Soviet Union during World War II, but never deployed.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] During the Cold War, the US produced the M23 chemical mine containing VX.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] A small explosive charge burst the mine open and dispersed the chemical when the mine was triggered.
[src:bb-gun/anti-personnel-mines] Anti-personnel mines are a typical example of subject-matter excluded from patentability under the European Patent Convention, because the publication or exploitation of such inventions are contrary to the "ordre public" and/or morality (Article 53(a) EPC).
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] Most modern anti-aircraft (AA) weapons systems are optimised for short-, medium-, or long-range air defence, although some systems may incorporate multiple weapons (such as both autocannons and surface-to-air missiles).
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] 'Layered air defence' usually refers to multiple 'tiers' of air defence systems which, when combined, an airborne threat must penetrate to reach its target; this defence is usually accomplished via the combined use of systems optimised for either short-, medium-, or long-range air defence.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] In some countries, such as Britain and Germany during the Second World War, the Soviet Union, and modern NATO and the United States, ground-based air defence and air defence aircraft have been under integrated command and control.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] However, while overall air defence may be for homeland defence (including military facilities), forces in the field, wherever they are, provide their own defences against airborne threats.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] It may also be called *counter-air*, *anti-air*, *AA*, *flak*, *layered air defence* or *air defence forces*.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] The term *air defence* was probably first used by the UK when Air Defence of Great Britain (ADGB) was created as a Royal Air Force command in 1925.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] However, arrangements in the UK were also called *anti-aircraft*, abbreviated as *AA*, a term that remained in general use into the 1950s.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] After the First World War it was sometimes prefixed by "light" or "heavy" (*LAA* or *HAA*) to classify a type of gun or unit.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] NATO defines anti-aircraft warfare (AAW) as "measures taken to defend a maritime force against attacks by airborne weapons launched from aircraft, ships, submarines and land-based sites".
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] In some armies the term *all-arms air defence* (AAAD) is used for air defence by nonspecialist troops.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] Other terms from the late 20th century include "ground based air defence" (GBAD) with related terms "short range air defence" (SHORAD) and man-portable air-defence system (MANPADS).
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] Anti-aircraft missiles are variously called surface-to-air missiles, ("SAMs") and surface-to-air guided weapons (SAGWs).
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] Examples are the RIM-66 Standard, Raytheon Standard Missile 6, or the MBDA Aster missile.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] Non-English terms for air defence include the German term *Flak* or *FlaK* (*Fliegerabwehrkanone*, lit.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] 'aircraft defence cannon', also cited as *Flugabwehrkanone*), and the Russian term *Protivovozdushnaya oborona* (Russian: Противовозду́шная оборо́на, lit.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] 'anti-air defence'), abbreviated as PVO.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] In Russian, the AA systems are called *zenitnye* (i.e., 'pointing to zenith') systems.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] In French, air defence is called *Défense contre les aéronefs (DCA)*, lit.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] The maximum distance at which a gun or missile can engage an aircraft is an important figure.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] However, many different definitions are used and unless the same definition is used, performance of different guns or missiles cannot be compared.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] For AA guns only the ascending part of the trajectory can be usefully used.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] One term is "ceiling", the maximum ceiling being the height a projectile would reach if fired vertically, not practically useful in itself as few AA guns are able to fire vertically, and the maximum fuse duration may be too short, but potentially useful as a standard to compare different weapons.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] The British adopted "effective ceiling", meaning the altitude at which a gun could deliver a series of shells against a moving target; this could be constrained by maximum fuse running time as well as the gun's capability.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] By the late 1930s the British definition was "that height at which a directly approaching target at 400 mph [640 km/h] can be engaged for 20 seconds before the gun reaches 70 degrees elevation".
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] The essence of air defence is to detect hostile aircraft and destroy them.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] The critical issue is to hit a target moving in three-dimensional space; an attack must not only match these three coordinates, but must do so at the time the target is at that position.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] This means that projectiles either have to be guided to hit the target, or aimed at the predicted position of the target at the time the projectile reaches it, taking into account the speed and direction of both the target and the projectile.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] Improvements were made to sensors, technical fire control, weapons, and command and control.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] At the start of the 20th century these were either very primitive or non-existent.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] Initially sensors were optical and acoustic devices developed during World War I and continued into the 1930s, but were quickly superseded by radar, which in turn was supplemented by optoelectronics in the 1980s.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] Command and control remained primitive until the late 1930s, when Britain created the integrated Dowding system for ADGB that linked the ground-based air defence of the British Army's Anti-Aircraft Command, although field-deployed air defence relied on less sophisticated arrangements.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] NATO later called these arrangements an "air defence ground environment", defined as "the network of ground radar sites and command and control centres within a specific theatre of operations which are used for the tactical control of air defence operations".
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] Rules of engagement are critical to prevent air defences engaging friendly or neutral aircraft.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] Their use is assisted but not governed by identification friend or foe (IFF) electronic devices originally introduced during the Second World War.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] While these rules originate at the highest authority, different rules can apply to different types of air defence covering the same area at the same time.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] AAAD usually operates under the tightest rules.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] Until the 1950s, guns firing ballistic munitions were the standard weapon; guided missiles then became dominant, except at the very shortest ranges.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] However, the type of shell or warhead and its fuzing and, with missiles, the guidance arrangement were and are varied.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] Targets are not always easy to destroy; nonetheless, damaged aircraft may be forced to abort their mission and, even if they manage to return and land in friendly territory, may be out of action for days or permanently.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] Ignoring small arms and smaller machine-guns, ground-based air defence guns have varied in caliber from 20 mm to at least 152 mm.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] Passive air defence is defined by NATO as "Passive measures taken for the physical defence and protection of personnel, essential installations and equipment in order to minimise the effectiveness of air and/or missile attack".
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] It remains a vital activity by ground forces and includes camouflage and concealment to avoid detection by reconnaissance and attacking aircraft.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] Measures such as camouflaging important buildings were common in the Second World War.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] During the Cold War the runways and taxiways of some airfields were painted green.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] While navies are usually responsible for their own air defence—at least for ships at sea—organisational arrangements for land-based air defence vary between nations and over time.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] The most extreme case was the Soviet Union and this model may still be followed in some countries: it was a separate service, on a par with the army, navy, or air force.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] In the Soviet Union, this was called *Voyska PVO*, and had both fighter aircraft, separate from the air force, and ground-based systems.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] This was divided into two arms, *PVO Strany,* the Strategic Air defence Service responsible for Air Defence of the Homeland, created in 1941 and becoming an independent service in 1954, and *PVO SV,* Air Defence of the Ground Forces.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] Subsequently, these became part of the air force and ground forces respectively.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] At the other extreme, the United States Army has an Air Defense Artillery Branch that provides ground-based air defence for both homeland and the army in the field; however, it is operationally under the Joint Force Air Component Commander.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] Many other nations also deploy an air-defence branch in the army.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] Some, such as Japan or Israel, choose to integrate their ground based air defence systems into their air force.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] In Britain and some other armies, the single artillery branch has been responsible for both home and overseas ground-based air defence, although there was divided responsibility with the Royal Navy for air defence of the British Isles in World War I.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] However, during the Second World War, the RAF Regiment was formed to protect airfields everywhere, and this included light air defences.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] In the later decades of the Cold War this included the United States Air Force's operating bases in the UK.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] All ground-based air defence was removed from Royal Air Force (RAF) jurisdiction in 2004.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] The British Army's Anti-Aircraft Command was disbanded in March 1955, but during the 1960s and 1970s the RAF's Fighter Command operated long-range air-defence missiles to protect key areas in the UK.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] During World War II, the Royal Marines also provided air defence units; formally part of the mobile naval base defence organisation, they were handled as an integral part of the army-commanded ground based air defences.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] The basic air defence unit is typically a battery with 2 to 12 guns or missile launchers and fire control elements.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] These batteries, particularly with guns, usually deploy in a small area, although batteries may be split; this is usual for some missile systems.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] SHORAD missile batteries often deploy across an area with individual launchers several kilometres apart.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] When MANPADS is operated by specialists, batteries may have several dozen teams deploying separately in small sections; self-propelled air defence guns may deploy in pairs.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] Batteries are usually grouped into battalions or equivalent.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] In the field army, a light gun or SHORAD battalion is often assigned to a manoeuvre division.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] Heavier guns and long-range missiles may be in air-defence brigades and come under corps or higher command.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] Homeland air defence may have a full military structure.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] For example, the UK's Anti-Aircraft Command, commanded by a full British Army general was part of ADGB.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p01] At its peak in 1941–42 it comprised three AA corps with 12 AA divisions between them.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Army during the American Civil War compelled the Confederates to develop methods of combating them.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] These included the use of artillery, small arms, and saboteurs.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] They were unsuccessful, and internal politics led the United States Army's Balloon Corps to be disbanded mid-war.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The Confederates experimented with balloons as well.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Turks carried out the first ever anti-airplane operation in history during the Italo-Turkish War.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Although lacking anti-aircraft weapons, they were the first to shoot down an airplane by rifle fire.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The first aircraft to crash in a war was the one of Lieutenant Piero Manzini, shot down on 25 August 1912.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The earliest known use of weapons specifically made for the anti-aircraft role occurred during the Franco-Prussian War of 1870.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] After the disaster at Sedan, Paris was besieged and French troops outside the city started an attempt at communication via balloon.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Gustav Krupp mounted a modified 1-pounder (37 mm) gun – the *Ballonabwehrkanone* (Balloon defence cannon) or *BaK* — on top of a horse-drawn carriage for the purpose of shooting down these balloons.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] By the early 20th century balloon, or airship, guns, for land and naval use were attracting attention.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Various types of ammunition were proposed, high explosive, incendiary, bullet-chains, rod bullets and shrapnel.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The need for some form of tracer or smoke trail was articulated.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Fuzing options were also examined, both impact and time types.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Mountings were generally pedestal type but could be on field platforms.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Trials were underway in most countries in Europe but only Krupp, Erhardt, Vickers Maxim, and Schneider had published any information by 1910.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Krupp's designs included adaptations of their 65 mm 9-pounder, a 75 mm 12-pounder, and even a 105 mm gun.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Erhardt also had a 12-pounder, while Vickers Maxim offered a 3-pounder and Schneider a 47 mm.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The French balloon gun appeared in 1910, it was an 11-pounder but mounted on a vehicle, with a total uncrewed weight of two tons.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] However, since balloons were slow moving, sights were simple.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] But the challenges of faster moving aeroplanes were recognised.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] By 1913 only France and Germany had developed field guns suitable for engaging balloons and aircraft and addressed issues of military organisation.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Britain's Royal Navy would soon introduce the QF 3-inch and QF 4-inch AA guns and also had Vickers 1-pounder quick firing "pom-poms" that could be used in various mountings.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The first US anti-aircraft cannon was a 1-pounder concept design by Admiral Twining in 1911 to meet the perceived threat of airships, that eventually was used as the basis for the US Navy's first operational anti-aircraft cannon: the 3-inch/23 caliber gun.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] On 30 September 1915, troops of the Serbian Army observed three enemy aircraft approaching Kragujevac.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Soldiers fired at them with shotguns and machine-guns but failed to prevent them from dropping 45 bombs over the city, hitting military installations, the railway station and many other, mostly civilian, targets in the city.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] During the bombing raid, private Radoje Ljutovac fired his cannon at the enemy aircraft and successfully shot one down.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] It crashed in the city and both pilots died from their injuries.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The cannon Ljutovac used was not designed as an anti-aircraft gun; it was a slightly modified Turkish cannon captured during the First Balkan War in 1912.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] This was the first occasion in military history that a military aircraft was shot down with ground-to-air artillery fire.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] By December 1914 the Royal Naval Volunteer Reserve (RNVR) was manning AA guns and searchlights assembled from various sources at some nine ports.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The Royal Garrison Artillery (RGA) was given responsibility for AA defence in the field, using motorised two-gun sections.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The first were formally formed in November 1914.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Initially they used QF 1-pounder "pom-pom"s (37 mm versions of the Maxim Gun).
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] All armies soon deployed AA guns often based on their smaller field pieces, notably the French 75 mm and Russian 76.2 mm, typically simply propped up on some sort of embankment to get the muzzle pointed skyward.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The British Army adopted the 13-pounder quickly producing new mountings suitable for AA use, the 13-pounder QF 6 cwt Mk III was issued in 1915.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] It remained in service throughout the war but 18-pounder guns were lined down to take the 13-pounder shell with a larger cartridge producing the 13-pounder QF 9 cwt and these proved much more satisfactory.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] However, in general, these ad hoc solutions proved largely useless.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] With little experience in the role, no means of measuring target, range, height or speed the difficulty of observing their shell bursts relative to the target gunners proved unable to get their fuse setting correct and most rounds burst well below their targets.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The exception to this rule was the guns protecting spotting balloons, in which case the altitude could be accurately measured from the length of the cable holding the balloon.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Before the war it was recognised that ammunition needed to explode in the air.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Both high explosive (HE) and shrapnel were used, mostly the former.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Airburst fuses were either igniferious (based on a burning fuse) or mechanical (clockwork).
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Igniferious fuses were not well suited for anti-aircraft use.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The fuse length was determined by time of flight, but the burning rate of the gunpowder was affected by altitude.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The British pom-poms had only contact-fused ammunition.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Zeppelins, being hydrogen-filled balloons, were targets for incendiary shells and the British introduced these with airburst fuses, both shrapnel type-forward projection of incendiary "pot" and base ejection of an incendiary stream.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The British also fitted tracers to their shells for use at night.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Smoke shells were also available for some AA guns, these bursts were used as targets during training.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] German air attacks on the British Isles increased in 1915 and the AA efforts were deemed somewhat ineffective, so a Royal Navy gunnery expert, Admiral Sir Percy Scott, was appointed to make improvements, particularly an integrated AA defence for London.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The air defences were expanded with more RNVR AA guns, 75 mm and 3-inch, the pom-poms being ineffective.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The naval 3-inch was also adopted by the army, the QF 3-inch 20 cwt (76 mm), a new field mounting was introduced in 1916.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Since most attacks were at night, searchlights were soon used, and acoustic methods of detection and locating were developed.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] By December 1916 there were 183 AA sections defending Britain (most with the 3-inch), 74 with the BEF in France and 10 in the Middle East.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The problem was of successfully aiming a shell to burst close to its target's future position, with various factors affecting the shells' predicted trajectory.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] This was called deflection gun-laying, where "off-set" angles for range and elevation were set on the gunsight and updated as their target moved.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] In this method, when the sights were on the target, the barrel was pointed at the target's future position.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Range and height of the target determined fuse length.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The difficulties increased as aircraft performance improved.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The British dealt with range measurement first, when it was realised that range was the key to producing a better fuse setting.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] This led to the height/range finder (HRF), the first model being the Barr & Stroud UB2, a two-metre optical coincident rangefinder mounted on a tripod.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] It measured the distance to the target and the elevation angle, which together gave the height of the aircraft.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] These were complex instruments and various other methods were also used.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The HRF was soon joined by the height/fuse indicator (HFI), this was marked with elevation angles and height lines overlaid with fuse length curves, using the height reported by the HRF operator, the necessary fuse length could be read off.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] However, the problem of deflection settings — "aim-off" — required knowing the rate of change in the target's position.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Both France and the UK introduced tachymetric devices to track targets and produce vertical and horizontal deflection angles.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The French Brocq system was electrical; the operator entered the target range and had displays at guns; it was used with their 75 mm.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The British Wilson-Dalby gun director used a pair of trackers and mechanical tachymetry; the operator entered the fuse length, and deflection angles were read from the instruments.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] By the start of World War I, the 77 mm had become the standard German weapon, and came mounted on a large traverse that could be easily transported on a wagon.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Krupp 75 mm guns were supplied with an optical sighting system that improved their capabilities.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The German Army also adapted a revolving cannon that came to be known to Allied fliers as the "flaming onion" from the shells in flight.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] This gun had five barrels that quickly launched a series of 37 mm artillery shells.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] As aircraft started to be used against ground targets on the battlefield, the AA guns could not be traversed quickly enough at close targets and, being relatively few, were not always in the right place (and were often unpopular with other troops), so changed positions frequently.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Soon the forces were adding various machine-gun based weapons mounted on poles.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] These short-range weapons proved more deadly, and the "Red Baron" is believed to have been shot down by an anti-aircraft Vickers machine gun.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] When the war ended, it was clear that the increasing capabilities of aircraft would require better means of acquiring targets and aiming at them.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Nevertheless, a pattern had been set: anti-aircraft warfare would employ heavy weapons to attack high-altitude targets and lighter weapons for use when aircraft came to lower altitudes.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] World War I demonstrated that aircraft could be an important part of the battlefield, but in some nations it was the prospect of strategic air attack that was the main issue, presenting both a threat and an opportunity.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The experience of four years of air attacks on London by Zeppelins and Gotha G.V bombers had particularly influenced the British and was one of if not the main driver for forming an independent air force.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] As the capabilities of aircraft and their engines improved it was clear that their role in future war would be even more critical as their range and weapon load grew.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] However, in the years immediately after World War I, the prospect of another major war seemed remote, particularly in Europe, where the most militarily capable nations were, and little financing was available.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Four years of war had seen the creation of a new and technically demanding branch of military activity.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Air defence had made huge advances, albeit from a very low starting point.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] However, it was new and often lacked influential 'friends' in the competition for a share of limited defence budgets.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Demobilisation meant that most AA guns were taken out of service, leaving only the most modern.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] However, there were lessons to be learned.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] In particular the British, who had had AA guns in most theatres in action in daylight and used them against night attacks at home.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Furthermore, they had also formed an Anti-Aircraft Experimental Section during the war and accumulated large amounts of data that was subjected to extensive analysis.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] As a result, they published the two-volume *Textbook of Anti-Aircraft Gunnery* in 1924–1925.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Two assumptions underpinned the British approach to HAA fire; first, aimed fire was the primary method and this was enabled by predicting gun data from visually tracking the target and having its height.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Second, that the target would maintain a steady course, speed and height.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] This HAA was to engage targets up to 24,000 ft (7.3 km).
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Mechanical time fuses were required because the speed of powder burning varied with height, so fuse length was not a simple function of time of flight.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Automated fire ensured a constant rate of fire that made it easier to predict where each shell should be individually aimed.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] In 1925 the British adopted a new instrument developed by Vickers.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] It was a mechanical analogue computer – the Predictor AA No 1.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Given the target height, its operators tracked the target and the predictor produced bearing, quadrant elevation and fuse setting.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] These were passed electrically to the guns, where they were displayed on repeater dials to the layers who "matched pointers" (target data and the gun's actual data) to lay the guns.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] This system of repeater electrical dials built on the arrangements introduced by British coast artillery in the 1880s, and coast artillery was the background of many AA officers.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Similar systems were adopted in other countries and for example the later Sperry M3A3 in the US, was also used by Britain as the Predictor AA No 2.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Height finders were also increasing in size; in Britain, the 7 ft (2.1 m) optical base World War I Barr & Stroud UB 2 stereoscopic rangefinder was replaced by the 9 ft (2.7 m) optical base UB 7 and the 18 ft (5.5 m) base UB 10 (only used on static AA sites).
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Goertz in Germany and Levallois in France produced five-metre (16 ft) instruments.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] However, in most countries the main effort in HAA guns until the mid-1930s was improving existing ones, although various new designs were on drawing boards.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] From the early 1930s eight countries developed radar; these developments were sufficiently advanced by the late 1930s for development work on sound-locating acoustic devices to be generally halted, although equipment was retained.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Furthermore, in Britain the volunteer Observer Corps formed in 1925 provided a network of observation posts to report hostile aircraft flying over Britain.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Initially radar was used for airspace surveillance to detect approaching hostile aircraft.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] However, the German Würzburg radar put into use in 1940 was capable of providing data suitable for controlling AA guns, and the British Radar, Gun Laying, Mark I, was designed to be used on AA gun positions and was in use by 1939.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The Treaty of Versailles prevented Germany having AA weapons, and for example, the Krupps designers joined Bofors in Sweden.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Some World War I guns were retained and some covert AA training started in the late 1920s.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Germany introduced the 8.8 cm FlaK 18 in 1933, the 36 and 37 models followed with various improvements, but ballistic performance was unchanged.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] In the late 1930s the 10.5 cm FlaK 38 appeared, soon followed by the 39; this was designed primarily for static sites but had a mobile mounting, and the unit had 220 V 24 kW generators.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] In 1938 design started on the 12.8 cm FlaK.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Britain had successfully tested a new 3.6-inch gun, in 1918.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] In 1928 a 3.7-inch (94 mm) gun became the preferred solution, but it took six years to gain funding.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Production of the QF 3.7-inch gun began in 1937; this gun was used on mobile carriages with the field army and transportable guns on fixed mountings for static positions.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] At the same time the Royal Navy adopted a new 4.5-inch (113 mm) gun in a twin turret, which the army adopted in simplified single-gun mountings for static positions, mostly around ports where naval ammunition was available.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The performance of the new guns was limited by their standard fuse No 199, with a 30-second running time, although a new mechanical time fuse giving 43 seconds was nearing readiness.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] In 1939 a machine fuse setter was introduced to eliminate manual fuse setting.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The US ended World War I with two 3-inch AA guns and improvements were developed throughout the inter-war period.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] However, in 1924 work started on a new 105 mm static mounting AA gun, but only a few were produced by the mid-1930s because by this time work had started on the 90 mm AA gun, with mobile carriages and static mountings able to engage air, sea and ground targets.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] During the 1920s there was some work on a 4.7-inch which lapsed, but revived in 1937, leading to a new gun in 1944.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] While HAA and its associated target acquisition and fire control was the primary focus of AA efforts, low-level close-range targets remained and by the mid-1930s were becoming an issue.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Until this time the British, at RAF insistence, continued their use of World War I machine guns, and introduced twin MG mountings for AAAD.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The army was forbidden from considering anything larger than .50-inch.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] However, in 1935 their trials showed that the minimum effective round was an impact-fused 2 lb HE shell.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The following year they decided to adopt the Bofors 40 mm and a twin barrel Vickers 2-pounder (40 mm) on a modified naval mount.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The air-cooled Bofors was vastly superior for land use, being much lighter than the water-cooled "pom-pom", and UK production of the Bofors 40 mm was licensed.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The Predictor AA No 3, as the Kerrison Predictor was officially known, was introduced with it.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The 40 mm Bofors had become available in 1931.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] In the late 1920s the Swedish Navy had ordered the development of a 40 mm naval anti-aircraft gun from the Bofors company.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] It was light, rapid-firing and reliable, and a mobile version on a four-wheel carriage was soon developed.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Known simply as the 40 mm, it was adopted by some 17 different nations just before World War II and is still in use today in some applications such as on coastguard frigates.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Rheinmetall in Germany developed an automatic 20 mm in the 1920s and Oerlikon in Switzerland had acquired the patent to an automatic 20 mm gun designed in Germany during World War I.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Germany introduced the rapid-fire 2 cm FlaK 30 and later in the decade it was redesigned by Mauser-Werke and became the 2 cm FlaK 38.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Nevertheless, while 20 mm was better than a machine gun and mounted on a very small trailer made it easy to move, its effectiveness was limited.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The first, the 3.7 cm FlaK 18 developed by Rheinmetall in the early 1930s, was basically an enlarged 2 cm FlaK 30.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] It was introduced in 1935 and production stopped the following year.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] A redesigned gun 3.7 cm FlaK 36 entered service in 1938, it too had a two-wheel carriage.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] However, by the mid-1930s the Luftwaffe realised that there was still a coverage gap between 3.7 cm and 8.8 cm guns.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] They started development of a 5 cm gun on a four-wheel carriage.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] After World War I the US Army started developing a dual-role (AA/ground) automatic 37 mm cannon, designed by John M.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] It was standardised in 1927 as the T9 AA cannon, but trials quickly revealed that it was worthless in the ground role.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] However, while the shell was a bit light (well under 2 lbs) it had a good effective ceiling and fired 125 rounds per minute; an AA carriage was developed and it entered service in 1939 as the 37 mm gun M1.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] It proved prone to jamming, and was eventually replaced in AA units by the Bofors 40 mm.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The Bofors had attracted attention from the US Navy, but none were acquired before 1939.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Also, in 1931 the US Army worked on a mobile anti-aircraft machine mount on the back of a heavy truck having four .30 calibre water-cooled machine guns and an optical director.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] It proved unsuccessful and was abandoned.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The USSR introduced a new 76 mm *M1931* in 1937, an 85 mm *M1938* and developed the 37 mm M1939 (61-K), which appears to have been copied from the Bofors 40 mm.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] A Bofors 25 mm, essentially a scaled down 40 mm, was also copied as the 25 mm M1939.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] During the 1930s solid-fuel rockets were under development in the Soviet Union and Britain.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] In Britain the interest was for anti-aircraft fire, it quickly became clear that guidance would be required for precision.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] However, rockets, or "Unrotated Projectiles" as they were called, could be used for anti-aircraft barrages.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] A two-inch rocket using HE or wire obstacle warheads – the Z Battery – was introduced first to deal with low-level or dive bombing attacks on smaller targets such as airfields.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The three-inch was in development at the end of the inter-war period.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] WWI had been a war in which air warfare blossomed, but had not matured to the point of being a real threat to naval forces.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The prevailing assumption was that a few relatively small caliber naval guns could manage to keep enemy aircraft beyond a range where harm might be expected.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] In 1939 radio controlled target drones became available to the US Navy in quantity allowing a more realistic testing of existing anti-aircraft suites against actual flying and manoeuvring targets.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The results were sobering to an unexpected degree.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The United States was still emerging from the effects of the Great Depression and funds for the military had been sparse to the degree that 50% of shells used were still powder fused.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The US Navy found that a significant portion of its shells were duds or low order detonations (incomplete detonation of the explosive contained by the shell).
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Virtually every major country involved in combat in World War II invested in aircraft development.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The cost of aircraft research and development was small and the results could be large.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] So rapid was the performance leaps of evolving aircraft that the British High Angle Control System (HACS) was obsolete and designing a successor very difficult for the British establishment.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Electronics would prove to be an enabler for effective anti-aircraft systems and both the US and UK had a growing electronics industry.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] In 1939 radio controlled drones became available to actually test existing systems in British and American service.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The results were disappointing by any measure.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] High-level manoeuvring drones were virtually immune to shipboard AA systems.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The US drones could simulate dive bombing which showed the dire need for autocannons.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Japan introduced powered gliders in 1940 as drones but apparently was unable to dive bomb.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] There is no evidence of other powers using drones in this application at all.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] It may have caused a major underestimation of the threat and an inflated view of their AA systems.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Poland's AA defences were no match for the German attack, and the situation was similar in other European countries.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Significant AAW (Anti-Air Warfare) started with the Battle of Britain in the summer of 1940.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] QF 3.7-inch AA guns provided the backbone of the ground-based AA defences, although initially significant numbers of QF 3-inch 20 cwt were also used.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The Army's Anti-aircraft command, which was under operational command of RAF Fighter Command within Air Defence GB, grew to 12 AA divisions in three AA corps.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Bofors 40 mm guns entered service in increasing numbers.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] In addition, the RAF regiment was formed in 1941 with responsibility for airfield air defence, eventually with Bofors 40 mm as their main armament.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Fixed AA defences, using HAA and LAA, were established by the Army in key overseas places, notably Malta, Suez Canal and Singapore.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] While the 3.7-inch was the main HAA gun in fixed defences and the only mobile HAA gun with the field army, the QF 4.5-inch gun, manned by artillery, was used in the vicinity of naval ports and made use of the naval ammunition supply.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The 4.5-inch at Singapore had the first success in shooting down Japanese bombers.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Mid war QF 5.25-inch naval guns started being emplaced in some permanent sites around London.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] This gun was also deployed in dual-role coast defence/AA positions.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Germany's high-altitude needs were originally going to be filled by a 75 mm gun from Krupp, designed in collaboration with their Swedish counterpart Bofors, but the specifications were later amended to require much higher performance.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] In response Krupp's engineers presented a new 88 mm design, the FlaK 36.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] First used in Spain during the Spanish Civil War, the gun proved to be one of the best anti-aircraft guns in the world, as well as particularly deadly against light, medium, and even early heavy tanks.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] After the Dambusters raid in 1943 an entirely new system was developed that was required to knock down any low-flying aircraft with a single hit.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The first attempt to produce such a system used a 50 mm gun, but this proved inaccurate and a new 55 mm gun replaced it.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The system used a centralised control system including both search and targeting radar, which calculated the aim point for the guns after considering windage and ballistics, and then sent electrical commands to the guns, which used hydraulics to point themselves at high speeds.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Operators simply fed the guns and selected the targets.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] This system, modern even by today's standards, was in late development when the war ended.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The British had already arranged licence building of the Bofors 40 mm, and introduced these into service.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] These had the power to knock down aircraft of any size, yet were light enough to be mobile and easily swung.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The gun became so important to the British war effort that they even produced a movie, *The Gun*, that encouraged workers on the assembly line to work harder.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The Imperial measurement production drawings the British had developed were supplied to the Americans who produced their own (unlicensed) copy of the 40 mm at the start of the war, moving to licensed production in mid-1941.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Service trials demonstrated another problem however: that ranging and tracking the new high-speed targets was almost impossible.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] At short range, the apparent target area is relatively large, the trajectory is flat and the time of flight is short, allowing to correct lead by watching the tracers.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] At long range, the aircraft remains in firing range for a long time, so the necessary calculations can, in theory, be done by slide rules—though, because small errors in distance cause large errors in shell fall height and detonation time, exact ranging is crucial.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] For the ranges and speeds that the Bofors worked at, neither answer was good enough.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The solution was automation, in the form of a mechanical computer, the Kerrison Predictor.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Operators kept it pointed at the target, and the Predictor then calculated the proper aim point automatically and displayed it as a pointer mounted on the gun.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The gun operators simply followed the pointer and loaded the shells.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The Kerrison was fairly simple, but it pointed the way to future generations that incorporated radar, first for ranging and later for tracking.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Similar predictor systems were introduced by Germany during the war, also adding radar ranging as the war progressed.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] A plethora of anti-aircraft gun systems of smaller calibre was available to the German Wehrmacht combined forces, and among them the 1940-origin *Flakvierling* quadruple-20 mm-autocannon-based anti-aircraft weapon system was one of the most often-seen weapons, seeing service on both land and sea.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The similar Allied smaller-calibre air-defence weapons of the American forces were also quite capable.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Although of less power than Germany's 20 mm systems, the typical four or five combat batteries of an Army AAA battalion were often spread many kilometres apart from each other, rapidly attaching and detaching to larger ground combat units to provide welcome defence from enemy aircraft.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] AAA battalions were also used to help suppress ground targets.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Their larger 90 mm M3 gun would prove, as did the eighty-eight, to make an excellent anti-tank gun as well, and was widely used late in the war in this role.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Also available to the Americans at the start of the war was the 120 mm M1 gun *stratosphere gun*, which was the most powerful AA gun with an impressive 60,000 ft (18 km) altitude capability, however no 120 M1 was ever fired at an enemy aircraft.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The 90 mm and 120 mm guns continued to be used into the 1950s.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The United States Navy had also put some thought into the problem, When the US Navy began to rearm in 1939 in many ships the primary short ranged gun was the M2 .50 caliber machine gun.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] While effective in fighters at 300 to 400 yards this is point blank range in naval anti-aircraft ranges.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Production of the Swiss Oerlikon 20 mm had already started to provide protection for the British and this was adopted in exchange for the M2 machine guns.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] From December 1941 to January 1942, production had risen to not only cover all British requirements but also allowed 812 units to be actually delivered to the US Navy.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] By the end of 1942 the 20 mm had accounted for 42% of all aircraft destroyed by the US Navy's shipboard AA.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] However, the King Board had noted that the balance was shifting towards the larger guns used by the fleet.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The US Navy had intended to use the British pom-pom, however, the weapon required the use of cordite which BuOrd had found objectionable for US service.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Further investigation revealed that US powders would not work in the pom-pom.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Bureau of Ordnance was well aware of the Bofors 40 mm gun.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The firm York Safe and Lock was negotiating with Bofors to attain the rights to the air-cooled version of the weapon.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] At the same time Henry Howard, an engineer, and businessman became aware of it and contacted RADM W.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Furlong, chief of the Bureau of Ordnance.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] He ordered the Bofors weapon system to be investigated.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] York Safe and Lock would be used as the contracting agent.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The system had to be redesigned for both the English measurement system and mass production, as the original documents recommended hand fitting parts and drilling to shape.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] As early as 1928 the US Navy saw the need to replace the .50 caliber machine gun with something heavier.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Placed in quadruple mounts with a 500 rpm rate of fire it would have fit the requirements.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] However, the gun was suffering teething issues being prone to jamming.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] While this could have been solved the weight of the system was equal to that of the quad-mount Bofors 40 mm while lacking the range and power that the Bofors provided.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The gun was relegated to smaller less vital ships by the end of the war.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The 5"/38 naval gun rounded out the US Navy's AA suite.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] A dual purpose mount, it was used in both the surface and AA roles with great success.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Mated with the Mark 37 director and the proximity fuse it could routinely knock drones out of the sky at ranges as far as 13,000 yards.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] A 3"/50 MK 22 semiautomatic dual gun was produced but not employed before the end of the war and therefore beyond the scope of this article.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] However early marks of the 3"/50 were employed in destroyer escorts and on merchant ships.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] 3″/50 caliber guns (Marks 10, 17, 18, and 20) first entered service in 1915 as a refit to USS *Texas* (BB-35), and were subsequently mounted on many types of ships as the need for anti-aircraft protection was recognised.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] During World War II, they were the primary gun armament on destroyer escorts, patrol frigates, submarine chasers, minesweepers, some fleet submarines, and other auxiliary vessels, and were used as a secondary dual-purpose battery on some other types of ships, including some older battleships.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] They also replaced the original low-angle 4"/50 caliber guns (Mark 9) on "flush-deck" *Wickes* and *Clemson*-class destroyers to provide better anti-aircraft protection.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The gun was also used on specialist destroyer conversions; the "AVD" seaplane tender conversions received two guns; the "APD" high-speed transports, "DM" minelayers, and "DMS" minesweeper conversions received three guns, and those retaining destroyer classification received six.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The Germans developed massive reinforced-concrete blockhouses, some more than six stories high, which were known as *Hochbunker* 'high bunkers' or "*Flaktürme*" flak towers, on which they placed anti-aircraft artillery.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Those in cities attacked by the Allied land forces became fortresses.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Several in Berlin were some of the last buildings to fall to the Soviets during the Battle of Berlin in 1945.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The British built structures such as the Maunsell Forts in the North Sea, the Thames Estuary and other tidal areas upon which they based guns.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Some were outside territorial waters, and had a second life in the 1960s as platforms for pirate radio stations, while another became the base of a micronation, the Principality of Sealand.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Some nations started rocket research before World War II, including for anti-aircraft use.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Further research started during the war.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The first step was unguided missile systems like the British 2-inch RP and 3-inch, which was fired in large numbers from *Z batteries*, and were also fitted to warships.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The firing of one of these devices during an air raid is suspected to have caused the Bethnal Green disaster in 1943.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Facing the threat of Japanese Kamikaze attacks the British and US developed surface-to-air rockets like British Fairey Stooge or the American Lark as counter measures, but none of them were ready at the end of the war.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The Germans missile research was the most advanced of the war as the Germans put considerable effort in the research and development of rocket systems for all purposes.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Among them were several guided and unguided systems.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Unguided systems involved the Fliegerfaust (literally "aircraft fist") rocket launcher as the first MANPADS.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Guided systems were several sophisticated radio, wire, or radar guided missiles like the *Wasserfall* ('waterfall') rocket.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Owing to the severe war situation for Germany all of those systems were only produced in small numbers and most of them were only used by training or trial units.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Another aspect of anti-aircraft defence was the use of barrage balloons to act as physical obstacle initially to bomber aircraft over cities and later for ground attack aircraft over the Normandy invasion fleets.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The balloon, a simple blimp tethered to the ground, worked in two ways.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Firstly, it and the steel cable were a danger to any aircraft that tried to fly among them.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Secondly, to avoid the balloons, bombers had to fly at a higher altitude, which was more favourable for the guns.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Barrage balloons were limited in application, and had minimal success at bringing down aircraft, being largely immobile and passive defences.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The Allies' most advanced technologies were showcased by the anti-aircraft defence against the German V-1 cruise missiles (V stands for *Vergeltungswaffe*, 'retaliation weapon').
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The 419th and 601st anti-aircraft gun battalions of the US Army were first allocated to the Folkestone-Dover coast to defend London, and then moved to Belgium to become part of the "Antwerp X" project coordinated from the Le Grand Veneur in Keerbergen.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] With the liberation of Antwerp, the port city immediately became the highest priority target, and received the largest number of V-1 and V-2 missiles of any city.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The smallest tactical unit of the operation was a gun battery consisting of four 90 mm guns firing shells equipped with a radio proximity fuse.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Incoming targets were acquired and automatically tracked by SCR-584 radar,.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Output from the gun-laying radar was fed to the M9 Gun Director, an electronic analogue computer to calculate the lead and elevation corrections for the guns.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] With the help of these three technologies, close to 90% of the V-1 missiles, on track to the defence zone around the port, were destroyed in a single week in March 1945.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Post-war analysis demonstrated that even with newest anti-aircraft systems employed by both sides, the vast majority of bombers reached their targets successfully, on the order of 90%.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] While these figures were undesirable during the war, the advent of the nuclear bomb considerably altered the acceptability of even a single bomber reaching its target.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The developments during World War II continued for a short time into the post-war period as well.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] In particular the US Army set up a huge air defence network around its larger cities based on radar-guided 90 mm and 120 mm guns.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] US efforts continued into the 1950s with the 75 mm Skysweeper system, an almost fully automated system including the radar, computers, power, and auto-loading gun on a single powered platform.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The Skysweeper replaced all smaller guns then in use in the Army, notably the 40 mm Bofors.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] By 1955, the US military deemed the 40 mm Bofors obsolete due to its reduced capability to shoot down jet powered aircraft, and turned to SAM development, with the Nike Ajax and the RSD-58.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] In Europe NATO's Allied Command Europe developed an integrated air defence system, NATO Air Defence Ground Environment (NADGE), that later became the NATO Integrated Air Defence System.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The introduction of the guided missile resulted in a significant shift in anti-aircraft strategy.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Although Germany had been desperate to introduce anti-aircraft missile systems, none became operational during World War II.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Following several years of post-war development, however, these systems began to mature into viable weapons.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The US started an upgrade of their defences using the Nike Ajax missile, and soon the larger anti-aircraft guns disappeared.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The same thing occurred in the USSR after the introduction of their SA-2 Guideline systems.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] As this process continued, the missile found itself being used for more and more of the roles formerly filled by guns.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] First to go were the large weapons, replaced by equally large missile systems of much higher performance.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Smaller missiles soon followed, eventually becoming small enough to be mounted on armoured cars and tank chassis.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] These started replacing, or at least supplanting, similar gun-based SPAAG systems in the 1960s, and by the 1990s had replaced almost all such systems in modern armies.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Man-portable missiles, MANPADS, as they are known today, were introduced in the 1960s and have supplanted or replaced even the smallest guns in most advanced armies.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] In the 1982 Falklands War, the Argentine armed forces deployed the newest west European weapons including the 35 mm Oerlikon GDF-002 twin cannon and Roland missile.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] The Rapier missile system was the primary GBAD system, used by both British artillery and RAF regiment, a few brand-new FIM-92 Stinger were used by British special forces.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Both sides also used the Blowpipe missile.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] British naval missiles used included Sea Dart and the older Sea Slug longer range systems, SeaCat and the new Sea Wolf short range systems.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] Machine guns in AA mountings were used both ashore and afloat.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] During the 2008 South Ossetia war air power faced off against powerful SAM systems, like the 1980s Buk-M1.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] In February 2018, an Israeli F-16 fighter was downed in the Golan Heights province, after it had attacked an Iranian target in Syria.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p02] In 2006, Israel also lost a helicopter over Lebanon, shot down by a Hezbollah rocket.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Although the firearms used by the infantry, particularly machine guns, can be used to engage low altitude air targets, on occasion with notable success, their effectiveness is generally limited and the muzzle flashes reveal infantry positions.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Speed and altitude of modern jet aircraft limit target opportunities, and critical systems may be armoured in aircraft designed for the ground attack role.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] The shells fired by these weapons are usually fitted with different types of fuses (barometric, time-delay, or proximity) to explode close to the airborne target, releasing a shower of fast metal fragments.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] For shorter-range work, a lighter weapon with a higher rate of fire is required, to increase a hit probability on a fast airborne target.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Weapons between 20 mm and 40 mm calibre have been widely used in this role.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Smaller weapons, typically .50 calibre or even 8 mm rifle calibre guns have been used in the smallest mounts.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Unlike the heavier guns, these smaller weapons are in widespread use due to their low cost and ability to quickly follow the target.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Classic examples of autocannons and large calibre guns are the 40 mm autocannon from Bofors and the 8.8 cm FlaK 18, 36 gun designed by Krupp.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Artillery weapons of this sort have for the most part been superseded by the effective surface-to-air missile systems that were introduced in the 1950s, although they were still retained by many nations.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Land-based SAMs can be deployed from fixed installations or mobile launchers, either wheeled or tracked.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] The tracked vehicles are usually armoured vehicles specifically designed to carry SAMs.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Larger SAMs may be deployed in fixed launchers, but can be towed/re-deployed at will.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] The SAMs launched by individuals are known in the United States as the Man-Portable Air Defence Systems (MANPADS).
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] MANPADS of the former Soviet Union have been exported around the World, and can be found in use by many armed forces.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Targets for non-ManPAD SAMs will usually be acquired by air-search radar, then tracked before/while a SAM is "locked-on" and then fired.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Potential targets, if they are military aircraft, will be identified as friend or foe before being engaged.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] The developments in the latest and relatively cheap short-range missiles have begun to replace autocannons in this role.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] The interceptor aircraft (or simply interceptor) is a type of fighter aircraft designed specifically to intercept and destroy enemy aircraft, particularly bombers, usually relying on high speed and altitude capabilities.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] A number of jet interceptors such as the F-102 Delta Dagger, the F-106 Delta Dart, and the MiG-25 were built in the period starting after the end of World War II and ending in the late 1960s, when they became less important due to the shifting of the strategic bombing role to ICBMs.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Invariably the type is differentiated from other fighter aircraft designs by higher speeds and shorter operating ranges, as well as much reduced ordnance payloads.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] The radar systems use electromagnetic waves to identify the range, altitude, direction, or speed of aircraft and weather formations to provide tactical and operational warning and direction, primarily during defensive operations.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] In their functional roles they provide target search, threat detection, guidance, reconnaissance, navigation, instrumentation, and weather reporting support to combat operations.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] An *anti-UAV defence system* (AUDS) is a system for defence against military unmanned aerial vehicles.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] A variety of designs have been developed, using lasers, net-guns and air-to-air netting, signal jamming, and hi-jacking by means of in-flight hacking.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Anti-UAV defence systems have been deployed against ISIL drones during the Battle of Mosul (2016–2017).
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Alternative approaches for dealing with UAVs have included using a shotgun at close range, and for smaller drones, training eagles to snatch them from the air.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] This only works on relatively small UAVs and loitering munitions (also called "suicide drones").
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Larger UCAVs such as the MQ-1 Predator can be (and frequently are) shot down like manned aircraft of similar sizes and flight profiles.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] The US Navy began its railgun project in 2005, with tests in December 2010 achieving a world record muzzle energy of 33 MJ (24×10^6 ft⋅lbf), launching a 10.4 kg (23 lb) projectile at 2.5 km/s (8,200 ft/s).
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] This gun was planned to fire up to 10 times a minute, with self-guided projectiles hitting 5 m (16 ft) targets at 200 nautical miles (370 km) when ready, projected to be between 2020 and 2025.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] However, funding was pulled from the program in mid-2021, though the projectile's development was continued for use in conventional guns.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] The Japanese Maritime Self-Defense Force conducting the first known successful test firing of a railgun at sea in October 2023, with the 40 mm (1.6 in) gun firing 320-gram (0.71 lb) projectiles at over 2,000 metres per second (4,500 mph).
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] The railgun is mounted in a turret aboard the experimental ship JS Asuka, and is designed to be used against surface targets as well as hypersonic missiles.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Upsetting this development to all-missile systems is the current move to stealth aircraft.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Long range missiles depend on long-range detection to provide significant lead.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Stealth designs cut detection ranges so much that the aircraft is often never even seen, and when it is, it is often too late for an intercept.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Systems for detection and tracking of stealthy aircraft are a major problem for anti-aircraft development.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] However, as stealth technology grows, so does anti-stealth technology.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Multiple transmitter radars such as those from bistatic radars and low-frequency radars are said to have the capabilities to detect stealth aircraft.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Advanced forms of thermographic cameras such as those that incorporate QWIPs would be able to optically see a stealth aircraft regardless of the aircraft's radar cross-section (RCS).
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] In addition, side-looking radars, high-powered optical satellites, and sky-scanning, high-aperture, high sensitivity radars such as radio telescopes, would all be able to narrow down the location of a stealth aircraft under certain parameters.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] The newest SAMs have a claimed ability to be able to detect and engage stealth targets, with the most notable being the Russian S-400, which is claimed to be able to detect a target with a 0.05-square metre RCS from 90 km away.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Another potential weapon system for anti-aircraft use is the laser.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Although air planners have imagined lasers in combat since the late 1960s, only the most modern laser systems are currently reaching what could be considered "experimental usefulness".
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] In particular the Tactical High Energy Laser can be used in the anti-aircraft and anti-missile role.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Most Western and Commonwealth militaries integrate air defence purely with the traditional services of the military (i.e. army, navy and air force), as a separate arm or as part of artillery.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] In the British Army for instance, air defence is part of the artillery arm, while in the Pakistan Army, it was split off from the artillery to form a separate arm of its own in 1990.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] This is in contrast to some (largely communist or ex-communist) countries where not only are there provisions for air defence in the army, navy and air force but there are specific branches that deal only with the air defence of territory, for example, the Soviet PVO Strany.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] The USSR also had a separate strategic rocket force in charge of nuclear intercontinental ballistic missiles.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Smaller boats and ships typically have machine-guns or fast cannons, which can often be deadly to low-flying aircraft if linked to a radar-directed fire-control system radar-controlled cannon for point defence.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Some vessels like Aegis-equipped destroyers and cruisers are as much a threat to aircraft as any land-based air defence system.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] In general, naval vessels should be treated with respect by aircraft, however the reverse is equally true.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Carrier battle groups are especially well defended, as not only do they typically consist of many vessels with heavy air defence armament but they are also able to launch fighter jets for combat air patrol overhead to intercept incoming airborne threats.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Some modern submarines, such as the Type 212 submarines of the German Navy, are equipped with surface-to-air missile systems, since helicopters and anti-submarine warfare aircraft are significant threats.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] The subsurface launched anti-air missile was first purposed by US Navy Rear Admiral Charles B.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Layered air defence in naval tactics, especially within a carrier group, is often built around a system of concentric layers with the aircraft carrier at the centre.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] The outer layer will usually be provided by the carrier's aircraft, specifically its AEW&C aircraft combined with the CAP.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Finally, virtually every modern warship will be fitted with small-calibre guns, including a CIWS, which is usually a radar-controlled Gatling gun of between 20 mm and 30 mm calibre capable of firing several thousand rounds per minute.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Armies typically have air defence in depth, from integral man-portable air-defence systems (MANPADS) such as the RBS 70, Stinger and Igla at smaller force levels up to army-level missile defence systems such as Angara and Patriot.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Often, the high-altitude long-range missile systems force aircraft to fly at low level, where anti-aircraft guns can bring them down.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] As well as the small and large systems, for effective air defence there must be intermediate systems.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] These may be deployed at regiment-level and consist of platoons of self-propelled anti-aircraft platforms, whether they are self-propelled anti-aircraft guns (SPAAGs), integrated air-defence systems like 2K22 Tunguska or all-in-one surface-to-air missile platforms like Roland or SA-8 Gecko.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] On a national level the United States Army was atypical in that it was primarily responsible for the missile air defences of the Continental United States with systems such as Project Nike.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Air defence by air forces is typically provided by fighter jets carrying air-to-air missiles.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] However, most air forces choose to augment airbase defence with surface-to-air missile systems as they are such valuable targets and subject to attack by enemy aircraft.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] In addition, some countries choose to put all air defence responsibilities under the air force.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Area air defence, the air defence of a specific area or location, (as opposed to point defence), have historically been operated by both armies (Anti-Aircraft Command in the British Army, for instance) and Air Forces (the United States Air Force's CIM-10 Bomarc).
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Area defence systems have medium to long range and can be made up of various other systems and networked into an area defence system (in which case it may be made up of several short range systems combined to effectively cover an area).
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] An example of area defence is the defence of Saudi Arabia and Israel by MIM-104 Patriot missile batteries during the first Gulf War, where the objective was to cover populated areas.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Most modern air defence systems are fairly mobile.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Even the larger systems tend to be mounted on trailers and are designed to be fairly quickly broken down or set up.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] In the past, this was not always the case.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Early missile systems were cumbersome and required much infrastructure; many could not be moved at all.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] With the diversification of air defence there has been much more emphasis on mobility.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Most modern systems are usually either self-propelled (i.e. guns or missiles are mounted on a truck or tracked chassis) or towed.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Even systems that consist of many components (transporter/erector/launchers, radars, command posts etc.) benefit from being mounted on a fleet of vehicles.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] In general, a fixed system can be identified, attacked and destroyed whereas a mobile system can show up in places where it is not expected.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Soviet systems especially concentrate on mobility, after the lessons learnt in the Vietnam War between the US and Vietnam with the SA-2 Guideline.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Many nations have developed significant tactics for air defence suppression.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Dedicated weapons such as anti-radiation missiles and advanced electronics intelligence and electronic countermeasures platforms seek to suppress or negate the effectiveness of an opposing air-defence system.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] It is an arms race; as better jamming, countermeasures and anti-radiation weapons are developed, so are better SAM systems with ECCM capabilities and the ability to shoot down anti-radiation missiles and other munitions aimed at them or the targets they are defending.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Stinger missiles supplied by the United States were used against the aircraft of the Soviet Union by the Afghan *mujahideen* during the Soviet occupation of Afghanistan in the Cold War.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Rocket-propelled grenades (RPGs) can be—and often are—used against hovering helicopters (e.g., by Somali militiamen during the 1993 Battle of Mogadishu.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Firing an RPG at steep angles poses a danger to the user, because the backblast from firing reflects off the ground.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] In Somalia, militia members sometimes welded a steel plate onto the exhaust end of an RPG's tube to deflect pressure away from the shooter when shooting up at US helicopters.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] RPGs are used in this role only when more effective weapons are not available.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Another example of using RPGs against helicopters is Operation Anaconda in March 2002 in Afghanistan.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Taliban insurgents defending Shah-i-Kot Valley used RPGs in a direct fire role against landing helicopters.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Four rangers were killed when their helicopter was shot down by an RPG, and SEAL team member Neil C.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] Roberts fell out of his helicopter when it was hit by two RPGs.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] In other instances helicopters have been shot down in Afghanistan during a mission in Wardak province.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] One feature that makes RPGs useful in air defence is that they are fused to automatically detonate at 920 m.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] If aimed into the air this causes the warhead to airburst which can release a limited but potentially damaging amount of shrapnel hitting a helicopter landing or taking off.
[src:bb-gun/antiaircraft-p03] A recent trend emerging during the Syrian Civil War is the use of ATGM against landing helicopters.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] A BB gun is a type of air gun that fires metallic spherical projectiles called **BBs** (not to be confused with similar-looking ball bearings), which are approximately the same size as BB-size lead birdshot used in shotguns (0.180 in or 4.6 mm in diameter).
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] Modern BB guns usually have a smoothbore barrel of 4.5 mm (0.177 in) caliber, and use steel balls that measure 4.3–4.4 mm (0.171–0.173 in) in diameter and 0.33–0.35 g (5.1–5.4 gr) in weight, usually zinc- or copper-plated for corrosion resistance.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] Some manufacturers still make the slightly larger traditional lead BBs that weigh around 0.48–0.50 g (7.4–7.7 gr), which are generally intended for use in rifled barrels (because lead is more malleable and exerts less wear on the rifling).
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] The term "BB gun" is sometimes incorrectly used to refer to airsoft guns, which shoot plastic pellets (also often referred to as "BBs") that are larger (usually 6 mm or 0.24 in in diameter) but much less dense than metal BBs, and have significantly lower ballistic performance.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] The term is sometimes mistakenly used to describe a pellet gun, which shoots diabolo-shaped (not spherical) lead projectiles at higher power and velocity.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] The term *BB* originated from the nomenclature of the size of lead shots used in a smoothbore shotgun.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] Size "BB" shots were nominally 0.180 in (4.6 mm), but tended to vary considerably in size because of the loose tolerances in shotshells.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] The largest shotgun pellet commonly used was named *00* or *double ought* and was used for hunting deer and thus called *buckshot*, while the smaller BB-sized shot was typically used to shoot small/medium-sized game birds and called *birdshot*.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] In 1886, the Markham Air Rifle Company in Plymouth, Michigan produced the first wooden-construct spring-piston air rifle design as a youth training gun, and used the BB lead shott as the chosen ammunition.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] Two years later, the neighbouring Plymouth Air Rifle Company (later renamed Daisy Manufacturing Company in 1895) introduced the first full-metal airgun that also fired BB shots – the Daisy BB Gun, which became a very popular household name because of successful marketing.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] Around 1900, Daisy changed their BB-size bore diameter to 0.175 in (4.4 mm), and began to market precision-made lead shot specifically for their BB guns.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] They called these "round shots", but the *BB* name was already well established, and consequently most users continued calling their guns *BB guns*, and the projectiles as *BB shots* or just *BBs*.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] Subsequently, the term *BB* became generic, and is used loosely referring to any small spherical projectiles of various calibers and materials.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] This includes bearing balls often utilized by anti-personnel mines, .177 caliber lead/steel shots used by air guns, plastic round balls (such as the pellets used by airsoft guns), small marbles and many others.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] It has become ubiquitous to refer to any steel ball, such as a BB, as a "*ball bearing*".
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] However, BBs should not be confused with a ball bearing, which is a mechanical component using small internal rolling balls to reduce friction between moving parts of machines.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] BB guns can use any of the operating mechanisms used for air guns.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] However, because the projectile inherently has limited accuracy and short effective range, only the simpler and less expensive mechanisms are generally used for guns designed to fire only BBs.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] Because the strength of the steel BB does not allow it to be swaged with the low propelling force used to accelerate it through the barrel, BBs are slightly smaller (4.3 to 4.4 mm (0.171 to 0.173 in)) than the internal diameter of the barrel (4.5 mm (0.177 in)).
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] This limits accuracy because little spin is imparted on the BB.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] It also limits range, because some of the pressurized gas used to accelerate the BB leaks around it and reduces the overall efficiency.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] Since a BB will easily roll unhindered down the barrel, it is common to find guns that use a magnet in the loading mechanism to hold the BB at the rear of the barrel until it is fired.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] The traditional and still most common powerplant for BB guns is the spring-piston pump, usually patterned after a lever-action rifle or a pump-action shotgun.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] The lever-action rifle was the first type of BB gun, and still dominates the inexpensive youth BB gun market.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] The Daisy Model 25, modeled after a pump-action shotgun with a trombone pump-action mechanism, dominated the low-price, higher-performance market for over 60 years (1914–1978).
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] Lever-action models generally have very low velocities, around 84 m/s (275 ft/s), a result of the weak springs used to keep cocking efforts low for use by youths.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] The Daisy Model 25 typically achieved the highest velocities of its day, ranging from 114 to 145 m/s (375 to 475 ft/s).
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] Multiple-pump pneumatic guns are also common.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] Many pneumatic pellet guns provide the ability to use BBs as a cheaper alternative to lead shot.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] Some of these guns have rifled barrels, but the slightly undersized BBs do not swage in the barrel, so the rifling does not impart a significant spin.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] These are the types of guns that will benefit most from using precision lead BB shot.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] Pneumatic BB guns can also attain higher velocities than traditional spring-piston types.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] The last common type of power for BB guns is compressed gas, most commonly the Powerlet cartridges.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] The powerlet is a disposable metal gas cylinder containing 12 grams (185 gr) of compressed carbon dioxide, with a self-contained valve to release the CO2 which expands to propel the BB.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] These are primarily used in BB pistols, and are capable of rapid firing unlike spring-piston or pneumatic types.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] A typical CO2 BB pistol uses a spring-loaded magazine to feed BBs, and a double-action trigger mechanism to chamber a BB and cock the hammer.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] However some guns (either to stay true to the original gun or to make the trigger pull easier) do have a single-action trigger.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] Either type of gun may also have blowback action, where CO2 will push the slide back in addition to firing a BB.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] When firing, the hammer strikes an internal valve linked to the CO2 source, which releases a measured amount of CO2 gas to fire the BB; this also gives it realistic recoil and muzzle report features.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] Many CO2 BB guns are patterned after popular firearms such as the Colt M1911, and can be used for training as well as recreation.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] Some gas-powered BB guns use a larger source of gas, and provide machine gun-like fire.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] These types, most notably the Shooting Star Tommy Gun (originally known as the Feltman) are commonly found at carnivals.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] The MacGlashan BB Gun was used to train antiaircraft gunners in the United States Army Air Corps and United States Navy during World War II.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] A popular commercial model was the Larc M-19, which used 1 pound (454 g) canisters of Freon-12 refrigerant.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] These types have very simple operating mechanisms, based on a venturi pump.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] The gas is released in a constant stream, and this is used to suck the BBs up into the barrel at rates as high as 3600 rounds per minute.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] BB guns can shoot faster than 60 m/s (200 ft/s), but are often less powerful than a conventional pellet airgun.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] Pellet airguns have the ability to fire considerably faster, even beyond 170 m/s (560 ft/s).
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] Although claims are often exaggerated, a few airguns can actually fire a standard 0.177 caliber lead pellet faster than 320 m/s (1,000 ft/s), but these are generally not BB-firing guns.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] A BB with a velocity of only 45 m/s (150 ft/s) has skin-piercing capability, and a velocity reaching 60 m/s (200 ft/s) can fracture bone.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] This is potentially lethal, and this potential increases with velocity, but also rapidly decreases with distance.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] The effective penetrating range of a BB gun with a muzzle velocity of 120 to 180 m/s (390 to 590 ft/s) is approximately 18 m (60 ft).
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] A person wearing jeans at this distance would not sustain serious injury.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] However, even at this distance a BB still might penetrate bare skin, and even if not, could leave a severe and painful bruise.
[src:bb-gun/bb-gun] The maximum range of a BB gun in the 120 to 180 m/s (390 to 590 ft/s) range is 100–200 metres approximately, provided the muzzle is elevated to the optimum angle.
